{"title_page": "1929 Georgia Bulldogs football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year=1929\n  |team=Georgia Bulldogs\n  |conference=Southern Conference\n  |short_conf=SoCon\n  |record=6\u20134\n  |conf_record=4\u20132\n  |head_coach=[[Harry Mehre]]\n  |hc_year=2nd\n  |captain=[[Ike Boland]]\n  |stadium=[[Sanford Stadium]] (30,000)\n}}\n{{1929 Southern Conference football standings}}\nThe '''1929 Georgia Bulldogs football team''' represented the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]] of the [[University of Georgia]] during the [[1929 college football season]]. The Bulldogs completed the season with a 6\u20134 record.<ref>{{cite web|title=1929 Georgia Bulldogs Schedule and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=SR/College Football|accessdate=July 29, 2015|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/georgia/1929-schedule.html}}</ref> The season featured the first game in newly completed [[Sanford Stadium]] on October 12 (a victory over [[1929 Yale Bulldogs football team|Yale]]) and Georgia's 100th loss (November 2 vs. [[1929 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]]).  In the 1920s, the Bulldogs compiled a record of 60\u201331\u20134 (a .653 winning percentage).\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 28\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Oglethorpe Stormy Petrels football team|Oglethorpe]]\n| site_stadium = [[Sanford Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Athens, Georgia|Athens, GA]]\n| score = 6\u201313\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 5\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1929|team=Furman Purple Hurricane|title=Furman}}\n| site_stadium = [[Sanford Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = Athens, GA\n| score = 27\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 12\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Yale Bulldogs football team|Yale]]\n| site_stadium = Sanford Stadium\n| site_cityst = Athens, GA\n| score = 15\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 19\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1929 North Carolina Tar Heels football team|North Carolina]]\n| site_stadium = [[Kenan Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill, NC]]\n| score = 19\u201312\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 26\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Florida Gators football team|Florida]]\n| gamename = [[Florida\u2013Georgia football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = [[Gator Bowl Stadium|Fairfield Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville, FL]]\n| score = 6\u201318\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 1\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]]\n| site_stadium = [[A. J. McClung Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus, GA]]\n| score = 15\u201321\n| attend = 15,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 9\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1929 NYU Violets football team|NYU]]\n| site_stadium = [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[The Bronx|Bronx, NY]]\n| score = 19\u201327\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 15\n| w/l = w\n| homecoming = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]]\n| gamename = [[Deep South's Oldest Rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = Sanford Stadium\n| site_cityst = Athens, GA\n| score = 24\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 28\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1930 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| gamename = [[Alabama\u2013Georgia football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = [[Legion Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham, AL]]\n| score = 12\u20130\n| attend = 25,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = December 6\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = [[1929 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]]\n| gamename = [[Clean, Old-Fashioned Hate]]\n| site_stadium = Sanford Stadium\n| site_cityst = Athens, GA\n| score = 13\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n}}\n*<small>Source: GeorgiaDogs.com: 1929 football schedule<ref name=\"1929schedule\">{{cite web | url=http://www.georgiadogs.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/1929-schedule.html | title=1929 Football Schedule | publisher=GeorgiaDogs.com| accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref></small>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cZPFcOrt45A Footage of Yale game]\n\n{{Georgia Bulldogs football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:1929 Southern Conference football season|Georgia Bulldogs]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football seasons]]\n[[Category:1929 in sports in Georgia (U.S. state)|Bulldogs]]\n\n\n{{Collegefootball-1920s-season-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year=1929\n  |team=Georgia Bulldogs\n  |conference=Southern Conference\n  |short_conf=SoCon\n  |record=6\u20134\n  |conf_record=4\u20132\n  |head_coach=[[Harry Mehre]]\n  |hc_year=2nd\n  |captain=[[Ike Boland]]\n  |stadium=[[Sanford Stadium]] (30,000)\n}}\n{{1929 Southern Conference football standings}}\nThe '''1929 Georgia Bulldogs football team''' represented the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]] of the [[University of Georgia]] during the [[1929 college football season]]. The Bulldogs completed the season with a 6\u20134 record.<ref>{{cite web|title=1929 Georgia Bulldogs Schedule and Results|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|work=SR/College Football|accessdate=July 29, 2015|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/georgia/1929-schedule.html}}</ref> The season featured the first game in newly completed [[Sanford Stadium]] on October 12 (a victory over [[1929 Yale Bulldogs football team|Yale]]) and Georgia's 100th loss (November 2 vs. [[1929 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]]).  In the 1920s, the Bulldogs compiled a record of 60\u201331\u20134 (a .653 winning percentage).\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = no\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 28\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Oglethorpe Stormy Petrels football team|Oglethorpe]]\n| site_stadium = [[Sanford Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Athens, Georgia|Athens, GA]]\n| score = 6\u201313\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 5\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = {{cfb link|year=1929|team=Furman Purple Hurricane|title=Furman}}\n| site_stadium = [[Sanford Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = Athens, GA\n| score = 27\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 12\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Yale Bulldogs football team|Yale]]\n| site_stadium = Sanford Stadium\n| site_cityst = Athens, GA\n| score = 15\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 19\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1929 North Carolina Tar Heels football team|North Carolina]]\n| site_stadium = [[Kenan Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill, NC]]\n| score = 19\u201312\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = October 26\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Florida Gators football team|Florida]]\n| gamename = [[Florida\u2013Georgia football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = [[Gator Bowl Stadium|Fairfield Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville, FL]]\n| score = 6\u201318\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 1\n| w/l = l\n| neutral = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]]\n| site_stadium = [[A. J. McClung Memorial Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus, GA]]\n| score = 15\u201321\n| attend = 15,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 9\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1929 NYU Violets football team|NYU]]\n| site_stadium = [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[The Bronx|Bronx, NY]]\n| score = 19\u201327\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 15\n| w/l = w\n| homecoming = y\n| opponent = [[1929 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]]\n| gamename = [[Deep South's Oldest Rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = Sanford Stadium\n| site_cityst = Athens, GA\n| score = 24\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = November 28\n| w/l = w\n| away = y\n| opponent = [[1930 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| gamename = [[Alabama\u2013Georgia football rivalry|rivalry]]\n| site_stadium = [[Legion Field]]\n| site_cityst = [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham, AL]]\n| score = 12\u20130\n| attend = 25,000\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = December 6\n| w/l = w\n| opponent = [[1929 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech]]\n| gamename = [[Clean, Old-Fashioned Hate]]\n| site_stadium = Sanford Stadium\n| site_cityst = Athens, GA\n| score = 13\u20130\n| attend = \n}}\n}}\n*<small>Source: GeorgiaDogs.com: 1929 football schedule<ref name=\"1929schedule\">{{cite web | url=http://www.georgiadogs.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/1929-schedule.html | title=1929 Football Schedule | publisher=GeorgiaDogs.com| accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref></small>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cZPFcOrt45A Footage of Yale game]\n\n{{Georgia Bulldogs football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:1929 Southern Conference football season|Georgia Bulldogs]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football seasons]]\n[[Category:1929 in sports in Georgia (U.S. state)|Bulldogs]]\n\n\n{{Collegefootball-1920s-season-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jweiss11", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSchedule:cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1929_Georgia_Bulldogs_football_team"}
{"title_page": "1797 Rugby School rebellion", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n[[File:Rugby School 850.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|[[Rugby School]] in 2004]]\nThe '''1797 Rugby School Rebellion''' was a mutiny of the boys at [[Rugby School]] after the headmaster, Dr Henry Ingles, demanded that boys from the fifth and sixth forms should pay for the repair of a local tradesman's windows after they had been smashed by the school's pupils. No!! rebellion saw many of the school windows broken and its furniture burnt before the boys withdrew to an island on the school grounds. A local [[justice of the peace]] read the [[Riot Act]], while soldiers crossed the island's moat from the rear and took the boys prisoner.\n\nThe rebellion was only one of several that took place at Rugby. The school was not alone in seeing disruption: several other public schools also saw trouble between 1710 and 1832.\n\n==Rugby School and discipline in 18th century public schools==\n[[Rugby School]]\u2014founded in 1567\u2014was one of the original seven [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public schools]], along with [[Winchester College|Winchester]], founded in 1382; [[Eton College]], founded in 1440; [[Shrewsbury School|Shrewsbury]], founded in 1552; [[Westminster School|Westminster]], founded in 1560; [[Harrow School|Harrow]], founded in 1571; [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]], founded in 1611.{{sfn|Honey|1989|p=152}}{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=35}}\n\nDiscipline at public schools in the 18th and 19th centuries was poor. According to the [[sociologist]]s Kenneth Sheard and [[Eric Dunning]], the reason lay in the balance of power between pupils and masters. Because the children of the [[upper class]] had previously been educated at home by tutors, these took the position of paid staff, and were therefore seen as socially inferior by their pupils. Sheard and Dunning consider that the tutors, \"confronted with pupils who were aristocrats and gentlemen,&nbsp;... became hesitant and uncertain in the execution of their role\".{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=38}}\n\nAt its worst, the breakdown in discipline led pupil rebellions at several institutions. In 1710 the pupils of Winchester rebelled over their beer ration. The school further rebelled in 1770, 1774, 1788 and 1793; Eton revolted in 1728, 1768 and 1783; Harrow had their protest in 1771; and Rugby's first revolt came in 1786. Some were peaceful\u2014the first Eton rebellion had been a walk out by pupils with no violence\u2014others were accompanied by threats, violence and damage to the school.{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=39}}{{sfn|Turner|2015|p=55}}\n\nAt the time of the rebellion, Rugby's [[headmaster]] was Dr Henry Ingles. He was appointed to the position in 1794 after having been the headmaster at Macclesfield School. A gloomy man and a strict disciplinarian, the pupils nicknamed him the Black Tiger.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=177}}{{sfn|Bradby|1900|p=44}}\n\n==November 1797==\n[[File:The Island, Rugby School.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The Island, a [[Bronze Age]] [[Tumulus|burial mound]], at Rugby School]]\nIn November 1797 Ingles found Astley, a pupil from Gascoigne's [[House system|boarding house]], firing cork bullets at the study windows of Mr Gascoigne, the housemaster. Ingles asked the boy where he had purchased the [[gunpowder]], and was informed it was from Rowell's, a local outlet that combined a grocers, booksellers and ironmongers.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|pp=182\u2013183}}{{sfn|Bradby|1900|p=44}} When Ingles confronted Rowell, the shopkeeper denied selling the powder and showed Ingles his sales book, in which the sale had been recorded as tea. Ingles took the shopkeeper's word over that of Astley, and the boy was flogged for lying. Astley told his friends about the flogging and the reason for it. Angered, Astley's friends smashed the windows of Rowell's.{{sfn|Staunton|1865|p=362}}{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=65}}\n\nWhen Ingles heard of the vandalism, he said that all the members of the fifth and sixth forms would pay for the damage. The boys drew up a [[Round-robin (document)|round robin]] response\u2014hiding the identity of the ringleaders\u2014in which they refused to pay.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=182}}{{efn|A \"[[Round-robin (document)|round robin]]\" is a document in which the signatures are written in a circle, in order to give none any prominence.{{sfn|\"Round Robin\". ''Oxford English Dictionary''}}}} The headmaster threatened punishment as a result. That Friday, after fourth lesson,{{efn|Fourth lesson would have finished either at 4 or 5{{nbsp}}pm.{{sfn|Hardy|1911|p=109}}}} the boys placed a home-made [[petard]]\u2014a small bomb used to blow open doors\u2014against a school door, which was blown off its hinges.{{sfn|Adams|2016|p=75}}{{sfn|\"Petard\". ''Oxford English Dictionary''}}{{efn|The door in question is given either as that of School House, one of the boarding houses,{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=183}}{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=65}} or Ingles's classroom door.{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=39}}}}\n\nThe following day the school bell was rung by the boys to signal the next part of the rebellion; at the same time [[Fagging|fags]] were sent to the boarding houses to rally boys to the main school building. The windows of the main building were all broken and the school's furniture\u2014including its [[Panelling#Wainscot panelling|wainscot panelling]]\u2014were thrown into the Close, the large main field in front of the school, where it was set alight. Also added to the pile were Ingles's books; Billy Plus, the school [[butler]] rescued some of the more expensive copies from the fire.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|pp=183\u2013184}}{{sfn|Bradby|1900|p=45}} The passage between School House, one of the boarding houses, and the main school building was nailed shut by the boys to stop Ingles\u2014who lived in at the boarding house\u2014gaining access into the school.{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=66}}\n\n[[File:Willoughby Cotton.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Willoughby Cotton]], one of the ringleaders, in later life]]\nAs Saturday afternoons were free of lessons, many of the masters had already left the school grounds. Ingles sent messages for them to return, but most were too far away to be found (two were fishing in the [[River Avon, Warwickshire|River Avon]], another was out shooting rabbits).{{sfn|Bradby|1900|pp=45\u201346}} Ingles sent a message to Mr Butlin, a local banker and the town's [[justice of the peace]]. It was market day in Rugby, so Butlin asked the horse-dealers, with their long [[droving]] whips to assist. He also asked an army recruitment party, headed by a [[sergeant]], for their assistance. An armed guard, with [[fixed bayonet]], was placed at School House, and the remainder of the soldiers, together with the horse-dealers and special constables, approached the Close.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=184}}\n\nThe rebellious schoolboys left the bonfire of furniture, and retreated to \"the Island\", a [[Bronze Age]] [[Tumulus|burial mound]] on the side of the Close, surrounded by a water [[moat]], up to {{convert|6|ft|m|1}} deep and {{convert|20|to|30|ft|m|1}} wide; after crossing the ditch, the boys drew up the wooden drawbridge.{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=66}}{{sfn|\"Rugby School \u2013 History\". Rugby School}} While Butlin distracted the boys, by reading them the [[Riot Act]], the soldiers circled round behind them and crossed the moat on the opposite side and took them prisoner.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|pp=184\u2013185}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nIngles had locked himself into School House while the events unfolded, but he emerged at the conclusion of the event. He immediately expelled the ringleaders and had many others flogged.{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=66}}{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=185}} One of the ringleaders was subsequently identified as [[Willoughby Cotton]] who entered the army shortly afterwards and led troops in Jamaica to put down a slave rebellion in 1831;{{sfn|Chichester|Lunt|2011}}{{sfn|Chandos|1984|p=179}} of those expelled, one later became a [[bishop]], another a [[marquess]].{{sfn|\"A Visit to Rugby\". ''Blackwood's Magazine''|p=554}}\n\nThe rebellion was not the last to occur in public schools, nor even at Rugby: the school was the location of further revolts by the boys in 1820 and 1822. Between 1797 and 1832 there were ten further rebellions in schools, four at Eton, three at Winchester and one each at Charterhouse, Harrow and Shrewsbury.{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=39}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{notes}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|colwidth=25em|refs=}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Adams|first=Matthew|title=Teaching Classics in English Schools, 1500-1840|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Qz5DAAAQBAJ&pg=PP1|year=2016|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|location=Newcastle upon Tyne|isbn=978-1-4438-8769-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bloxam|first1=Matthew|authorlink=Matthew Bloxam|title=Rugby: The School and the Neighbourhood|date=1889|publisher= Whittaker & Co|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/rugbyschoolandn00bloxgoog#page/n9/mode/2up|oclc=557371182|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bradby|first1=H. C.|title=Rugby|date=1900|publisher=George Bell & Sons|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/rugbyschool00braduoft#page/n7/mode/2up|oclc=826178165|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Chandos|first1=John|title=Boys Together: English Public Schools, 1800\u20131864|date=1984|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New York and London|url=https://archive.org/stream/boystogetherengl00chan#page/n0/mode/2up|isbn=978-0-300-03215-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Chichester|first1=H. M.|last2=Lunt|first2=James|title=Cotton, Sir Willoughby (1783\u20131860)|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/6434|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=27 May 2014|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/6434|year=2011|ref=harv}} {{ODNBsub}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Dunning|first1=Eric|authorlink1=Eric Dunning|last2=Sheard|first2=Kenneth|title=Barbarians, Gentlemen and Players: A Sociological Study of the Development of Rugby Football|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6R6eT4VgmksC&pg=PP1|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|location=Abingdon, Oxfordshire|isbn=978-0-7146-5353-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hardy|first1=H. H.|title=Rugby|date=1911|publisher=Sir Isaac Pitman & Sons|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/rugbyhardy00hard#page/n13/mode/2up|oclc=2150234|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Honey|first1=John|chapter=The Sinews of Society: The Public Schools as a 'System'|editor-last1=M\u00fcller|editor-first1=Detlef|editor-last2=Ringer|editor-first2=Fritz|editor-last3=Simon|editor-first3=Brian|title=The Rise of the Modern Educational System: Structural Change and Social Reproduction 1870-1920|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PHvkJJcyvpkC&pg=PP1|year=1989|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-36685-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite OED|Petard|access-date=26 July 2018|ref={{sfnRef|\"Petard\". ''Oxford English Dictionary''}}}}\n* {{Cite OED|Round Robin|access-date=26 July 2018|ref={{sfnRef|\"Round Robin\". ''Oxford English Dictionary''}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Rouse|first1=W. H. D.|authorlink=W. H. D. Rouse|title=A History of Rugby School|date=1898|publisher=Duckworth & Co|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofrugbysc00rousuoft#page/n7/mode/2up|oclc=932974800|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|title=Rugby School \u2013 History|url=https://www.rugbyschool.co.uk/about/history/|publisher=Rugby School|accessdate=26 July 2018|ref={{sfnRef|\"Rugby School \u2013 History\". Rugby School}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Staunton|first1=Howard|title=The Great Schools of England: An Account of the Foundation, Endowments, and Discipline of the Chief Seminaries of Learning in England|date=1865|publisher= Sampson Low, Son and Marston|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/greatschoolsofen00stauuoft#page/n5/mode/2up|oclc=249983144|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Turner|first=David|title=The Old Boys: The Decline and Rise of the Public School|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D2bbBgAAQBAJ&pg=PP1|year=2015|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven, CT|isbn=978-0-300-21313-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|title=A Visit to Rugby|journal=Blackwood's Magazine|date=May 1862|volume=91|issue=559|pages=537\u2013564|ref={{sfnRef|\"A Visit to Rugby\". ''Blackwood's Magazine''}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Rebellions in England]]\n[[Category:Rugby School]]\n[[Category:18th-century rebellions]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1797]]\n[[Category:1797 in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n[[File:Rugby School 850.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|[[Rugby School]] in 2004]]\nThe '''1797 Rugby School Rebellion''' was a mutiny of the boys at [[Rugby School]] after the headmaster, Dr Henry Ingles, demanded that boys from the fifth and sixth forms should pay for the repair of a local tradesman's windows after they had been smashed by the school's pupils. The rebellion saw many of the school windows broken and its furniture burnt before the boys withdrew to an island on the school grounds. A local [[justice of the peace]] read the [[Riot Act]], while soldiers crossed the island's moat from the rear and took the boys prisoner.\n\nThe rebellion was only one of several that took place at Rugby. The school was not alone in seeing disruption: several other public schools also saw trouble between 1710 and 1832.\n\n==Rugby School and discipline in 18th century public schools==\n[[Rugby School]]\u2014founded in 1567\u2014was one of the original seven [[Public school (United Kingdom)|public schools]], along with [[Winchester College|Winchester]], founded in 1382; [[Eton College]], founded in 1440; [[Shrewsbury School|Shrewsbury]], founded in 1552; [[Westminster School|Westminster]], founded in 1560; [[Harrow School|Harrow]], founded in 1571; [[Charterhouse School|Charterhouse]], founded in 1611.{{sfn|Honey|1989|p=152}}{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=35}}\n\nDiscipline at public schools in the 18th and 19th centuries was poor. According to the [[sociologist]]s Kenneth Sheard and [[Eric Dunning]], the reason lay in the balance of power between pupils and masters. Because the children of the [[upper class]] had previously been educated at home by tutors, these took the position of paid staff, and were therefore seen as socially inferior by their pupils. Sheard and Dunning consider that the tutors, \"confronted with pupils who were aristocrats and gentlemen,&nbsp;... became hesitant and uncertain in the execution of their role\".{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=38}}\n\nAt its worst, the breakdown in discipline led pupil rebellions at several institutions. In 1710 the pupils of Winchester rebelled over their beer ration. The school further rebelled in 1770, 1774, 1788 and 1793; Eton revolted in 1728, 1768 and 1783; Harrow had their protest in 1771; and Rugby's first revolt came in 1786. Some were peaceful\u2014the first Eton rebellion had been a walk out by pupils with no violence\u2014others were accompanied by threats, violence and damage to the school.{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=39}}{{sfn|Turner|2015|p=55}}\n\nAt the time of the rebellion, Rugby's [[headmaster]] was Dr Henry Ingles. He was appointed to the position in 1794 after having been the headmaster at Macclesfield School. A gloomy man and a strict disciplinarian, the pupils nicknamed him the Black Tiger.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=177}}{{sfn|Bradby|1900|p=44}}\n\n==November 1797==\n[[File:The Island, Rugby School.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|The Island, a [[Bronze Age]] [[Tumulus|burial mound]], at Rugby School]]\nIn November 1797 Ingles found Astley, a pupil from Gascoigne's [[House system|boarding house]], firing cork bullets at the study windows of Mr Gascoigne, the housemaster. Ingles asked the boy where he had purchased the [[gunpowder]], and was informed it was from Rowell's, a local outlet that combined a grocers, booksellers and ironmongers.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|pp=182\u2013183}}{{sfn|Bradby|1900|p=44}} When Ingles confronted Rowell, the shopkeeper denied selling the powder and showed Ingles his sales book, in which the sale had been recorded as tea. Ingles took the shopkeeper's word over that of Astley, and the boy was flogged for lying. Astley told his friends about the flogging and the reason for it. Angered, Astley's friends smashed the windows of Rowell's.{{sfn|Staunton|1865|p=362}}{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=65}}\n\nWhen Ingles heard of the vandalism, he said that all the members of the fifth and sixth forms would pay for the damage. The boys drew up a [[Round-robin (document)|round robin]] response\u2014hiding the identity of the ringleaders\u2014in which they refused to pay.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=182}}{{efn|A \"[[Round-robin (document)|round robin]]\" is a document in which the signatures are written in a circle, in order to give none any prominence.{{sfn|\"Round Robin\". ''Oxford English Dictionary''}}}} The headmaster threatened punishment as a result. That Friday, after fourth lesson,{{efn|Fourth lesson would have finished either at 4 or 5{{nbsp}}pm.{{sfn|Hardy|1911|p=109}}}} the boys placed a home-made [[petard]]\u2014a small bomb used to blow open doors\u2014against a school door, which was blown off its hinges.{{sfn|Adams|2016|p=75}}{{sfn|\"Petard\". ''Oxford English Dictionary''}}{{efn|The door in question is given either as that of School House, one of the boarding houses,{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=183}}{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=65}} or Ingles's classroom door.{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=39}}}}\n\nThe following day the school bell was rung by the boys to signal the next part of the rebellion; at the same time [[Fagging|fags]] were sent to the boarding houses to rally boys to the main school building. The windows of the main building were all broken and the school's furniture\u2014including its [[Panelling#Wainscot panelling|wainscot panelling]]\u2014were thrown into the Close, the large main field in front of the school, where it was set alight. Also added to the pile were Ingles's books; Billy Plus, the school [[butler]] rescued some of the more expensive copies from the fire.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|pp=183\u2013184}}{{sfn|Bradby|1900|p=45}} The passage between School House, one of the boarding houses, and the main school building was nailed shut by the boys to stop Ingles\u2014who lived in at the boarding house\u2014gaining access into the school.{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=66}}\n\n[[File:Willoughby Cotton.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Willoughby Cotton]], one of the ringleaders, in later life]]\nAs Saturday afternoons were free of lessons, many of the masters had already left the school grounds. Ingles sent messages for them to return, but most were too far away to be found (two were fishing in the [[River Avon, Warwickshire|River Avon]], another was out shooting rabbits).{{sfn|Bradby|1900|pp=45\u201346}} Ingles sent a message to Mr Butlin, a local banker and the town's [[justice of the peace]]. It was market day in Rugby, so Butlin asked the horse-dealers, with their long [[droving]] whips to assist. He also asked an army recruitment party, headed by a [[sergeant]], for their assistance. An armed guard, with [[fixed bayonet]], was placed at School House, and the remainder of the soldiers, together with the horse-dealers and special constables, approached the Close.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=184}}\n\nThe rebellious schoolboys left the bonfire of furniture, and retreated to \"the Island\", a [[Bronze Age]] [[Tumulus|burial mound]] on the side of the Close, surrounded by a water [[moat]], up to {{convert|6|ft|m|1}} deep and {{convert|20|to|30|ft|m|1}} wide; after crossing the ditch, the boys drew up the wooden drawbridge.{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=66}}{{sfn|\"Rugby School \u2013 History\". Rugby School}} While Butlin distracted the boys, by reading them the [[Riot Act]], the soldiers circled round behind them and crossed the moat on the opposite side and took them prisoner.{{sfn|Rouse|1898|pp=184\u2013185}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nIngles had locked himself into School House while the events unfolded, but he emerged at the conclusion of the event. He immediately expelled the ringleaders and had many others flogged.{{sfn|Bloxam|1889|p=66}}{{sfn|Rouse|1898|p=185}} One of the ringleaders was subsequently identified as [[Willoughby Cotton]] who entered the army shortly afterwards and led troops in Jamaica to put down a slave rebellion in 1831;{{sfn|Chichester|Lunt|2011}}{{sfn|Chandos|1984|p=179}} of those expelled, one later became a [[bishop]], another a [[marquess]].{{sfn|\"A Visit to Rugby\". ''Blackwood's Magazine''|p=554}}\n\nThe rebellion was not the last to occur in public schools, nor even at Rugby: the school was the location of further revolts by the boys in 1820 and 1822. Between 1797 and 1832 there were ten further rebellions in schools, four at Eton, three at Winchester and one each at Charterhouse, Harrow and Shrewsbury.{{sfn|Dunning|Sheard|2005|p=39}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{notes}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|colwidth=25em|refs=}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Adams|first=Matthew|title=Teaching Classics in English Schools, 1500-1840|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5Qz5DAAAQBAJ&pg=PP1|year=2016|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|location=Newcastle upon Tyne|isbn=978-1-4438-8769-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bloxam|first1=Matthew|authorlink=Matthew Bloxam|title=Rugby: The School and the Neighbourhood|date=1889|publisher= Whittaker & Co|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/rugbyschoolandn00bloxgoog#page/n9/mode/2up|oclc=557371182|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bradby|first1=H. C.|title=Rugby|date=1900|publisher=George Bell & Sons|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/rugbyschool00braduoft#page/n7/mode/2up|oclc=826178165|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Chandos|first1=John|title=Boys Together: English Public Schools, 1800\u20131864|date=1984|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New York and London|url=https://archive.org/stream/boystogetherengl00chan#page/n0/mode/2up|isbn=978-0-300-03215-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Chichester|first1=H. M.|last2=Lunt|first2=James|title=Cotton, Sir Willoughby (1783\u20131860)|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/6434|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=Oxford University Press|accessdate=27 May 2014|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/6434|year=2011|ref=harv}} {{ODNBsub}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Dunning|first1=Eric|authorlink1=Eric Dunning|last2=Sheard|first2=Kenneth|title=Barbarians, Gentlemen and Players: A Sociological Study of the Development of Rugby Football|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6R6eT4VgmksC&pg=PP1|year=2005|publisher=Routledge|location=Abingdon, Oxfordshire|isbn=978-0-7146-5353-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Hardy|first1=H. H.|title=Rugby|date=1911|publisher=Sir Isaac Pitman & Sons|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/rugbyhardy00hard#page/n13/mode/2up|oclc=2150234|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Honey|first1=John|chapter=The Sinews of Society: The Public Schools as a 'System'|editor-last1=M\u00fcller|editor-first1=Detlef|editor-last2=Ringer|editor-first2=Fritz|editor-last3=Simon|editor-first3=Brian|title=The Rise of the Modern Educational System: Structural Change and Social Reproduction 1870-1920|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PHvkJJcyvpkC&pg=PP1|year=1989|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-521-36685-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite OED|Petard|access-date=26 July 2018|ref={{sfnRef|\"Petard\". ''Oxford English Dictionary''}}}}\n* {{Cite OED|Round Robin|access-date=26 July 2018|ref={{sfnRef|\"Round Robin\". ''Oxford English Dictionary''}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Rouse|first1=W. H. D.|authorlink=W. H. D. Rouse|title=A History of Rugby School|date=1898|publisher=Duckworth & Co|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofrugbysc00rousuoft#page/n7/mode/2up|oclc=932974800|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|title=Rugby School \u2013 History|url=https://www.rugbyschool.co.uk/about/history/|publisher=Rugby School|accessdate=26 July 2018|ref={{sfnRef|\"Rugby School \u2013 History\". Rugby School}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Staunton|first1=Howard|title=The Great Schools of England: An Account of the Foundation, Endowments, and Discipline of the Chief Seminaries of Learning in England|date=1865|publisher= Sampson Low, Son and Marston|location=London|url=https://archive.org/stream/greatschoolsofen00stauuoft#page/n5/mode/2up|oclc=249983144|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Turner|first=David|title=The Old Boys: The Decline and Rise of the Public School|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D2bbBgAAQBAJ&pg=PP1|year=2015|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven, CT|isbn=978-0-300-21313-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|title=A Visit to Rugby|journal=Blackwood's Magazine|date=May 1862|volume=91|issue=559|pages=537\u2013564|ref={{sfnRef|\"A Visit to Rugby\". ''Blackwood's Magazine''}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Rebellions in England]]\n[[Category:Rugby School]]\n[[Category:18th-century rebellions]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1797]]\n[[Category:1797 in England]]\n", "name_user": "DrogbaHagi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1797_Rugby_School_rebellion"}
{"title_page": "Li Xian (actor)", "text_new": "{{Chinese name|[[Li (surname \u674e)|Li]]}}\n{{infobox person\n| name               = Li Xian\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = {{linktext|\u674e\u73b0}}\n| native_name_lang   = zh\n| pronunciation      = L\u01d0 Xi\u00e0n\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1991|10|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Xianning]], [[Hubei]]\n| nationality        = Chinese\n| alma_mater         = [[Beijing Film Academy]]\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2011\u2013present\n| agent              = Easy Entertainment\n| module             = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes|order=st\n| t= \u674e\u73fe | s= {{linktext|\u674e|\u73b0}} \n  | p = L\u01d0 Xi\u00e0n\n}}\n}}\n'''Li Xian''' ({{zh|s=\u674e\u73b0}}; born 19 October 1991)<ref name=\"The Beijing News\">{{cite news |last1=Liu |first1=Wei |title=Li Xian really wants to buy a cup of coffee |url=http://epaper.bjnews.com.cn/html/2019-12/17/content_774177.htm?div=-1 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |work=[[The Beijing News]] |publisher=The Beijing News |archiveurl=http://epaper.bjnews.com.cn/html/2019-12/17/content_774177.htm?div=-1/|archivedate=April 2, 2020|date=December 17, 2019 |pages=C04 |language=zh}}</ref> is a [[Mainland China]] actor. Made his feature film debut in 2011, and best known for his roles in the drama ''[[Go Go Squid!]]''.<ref name=xian>{{cite web |last1=Yau |first1=Elaine |title=Who is Li Xian, rising star of China TV hit Go Go Squid? |url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/entertainment/article/3021194/who-li-xian-rising-star-chinas-go-go-squid-hit-television |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=1 April 2020|archiveurl=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/entertainment/article/3021194/who-li-xian-rising-star-chinas-go-go-squid-hit-television|archivedate=August 5, 2019 |language=en |date=August 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLi Xian was born as Li Han ({{zh|s=\u674e\u73fe}}) on 19 October 1991 in [[Xianning]] City, and grew up in [[Jingzhou]] City, [[Hubei]] Province.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/ku/star_info_index.d.html?id=fyhvyie0226195|title=Li Xian Profile|website=Sina|language=zh}}</ref>  He studied at Jingzhou Middle School one of the best school in the City. In 2009 he thought to studying STEM subjects in college, but after failing the annual college entrance examination, he took the test again and enter the 2010 Department of [[Beijing Film Academy]] Performance Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/a/20160402/48317189_0.shtml||title=Jingzhou chubby turned into a half-cooked male god|script-title=zh:\u56fe\u6587\uff1a\u8346\u5dde\u5c0f\u80d6\u53d8\u8eab\u534a\u719f\u7537\u795e|website=ifeng|publisher=Chutian Metropolis Daily|date=April 2, 2016|language=zh}}</ref> For the convenience of entry, Li changed his name \"{{zh|s=\u665b}}\" into Xian \"{{zh|s=\u73b0}}\" which is mean \"present\".<ref name=\"The Beijing News\"/>  And he was also the first college student to be admitted to the academy in Jingzhou, Hubei Province.\n\n==Career==\n===2011\u20132018: Acting debut and Rising popularity===\nIn 2011, Li made his debut in the director Wang Jing's film, \"A Thousand Arrows Through Heart\" iIn which he played Li Baoli's son Xiaobao, a boy who is full of resentment towards his mother and has a restrained voice because of his father's early death. He got his first role in [[Feng Shui (2012 film)|''Feng Shui'']] when he was a sophomore at the academy. He got the role due to his age and the fact that the director, who was affiliated with the academy, was looking for someone from Hubei province, where Li was from.''<ref name=\"feng\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jznews.com.cn/comnews/system/2013/02/22/010784530.shtml|date=February 22, 2013|website=JZ News|language=zh|script-title=zh:\u300a\u4e07\u7bad\u7a7f\u5fc3\u300b\"\u5c0f\u5b9d\" \u6625\u8282\u56de\u8346\u5dde\u62dc\u5e74}}</ref>'' In 2013, he starred in the romance teen flick ''Singing When We Are Young'', produced by [[Andy Lau]].<ref name=sing>{{cite web|url=http://www.rbc.cn/bobo/2013-07/31/cms29689article.shtml|script-title=zh:\u4e13\u8bbf\u300a\u521d\u604b\u672a\u6ee1\u300b\u5bfc\u6f14\u674e\u5a1f\u3001\u6f14\u5458\u674e\u73b0|date=July 31, 2013|publisher=Radio Beijing Corporation |language=zh-cn}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014, Li made his small-screen debut in the omnibus web drama''City Of Fantasy''.<ref name=city>{{cite web|url=http://ent.163.com/14/1029/12/A9NLMTKS000333J5.html|script-title=zh:\u674e\u73b0\u300a\u5947\u5999\u4e16\u7eaa\u300b\u732e\u8367\u5e55\u521d\u543b \u6f14\u6280\u5927\u53d7\u597d\u8bc4|date=October 29, 2014|website=Netease|language=zh}}</ref>\nIn 2015, he co-starred with Chen Xiao, Du Tianhao and Liu Ruilin in the youth campus network drama \" Brothers Sleeping on My Upper Bunk \", and played the role of \"Loyal and Mighty Boy\" Xie Xun, a member of the 330 dormitory of Hudu University. In December, he starred in the music video of [[Zhang Jiao]]'s \" I'm Jiang Xiaobai 2016 \" and also starred in the second edition MV of [[Luhan]]\u2019s Medal .\n\nIn 2015, Li starred in the coming-of-age brotherhood web series ''[[Who Sleeps My Bro]]''.<ref name=sleep1>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/micro-reading/2016-03/28/content_24142835.htm|script-title=zh:\u300a\u7761\u5728\u6211\u4e0a\u94fa\u7684\u5144\u5f1f\u300b\u674e\u73b0\u51fa\u90535\u5e74\u5e05\u6c14\u8d70\u7ea2|date=March 28, 2016|website=China Daily|language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.ifeng.com/a/20160201/42571343_0.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u7761\u5728\u6211\u4e0a\u94fa\u7684\u5144\u5f1f\u300b\u6b63\u80fd\u91cf\u9752\u6625\u5267\u4e00\u6837\u662f|website=ifeng|date=February 1, 2016|language=zh}}</ref> The series was later adapted into a film starring the original cast. In the same year he participated in the Shanghai International Film Festival Red Carpet.<ref name=sleep>{{cite web|url=http://ent.ifeng.com/a/20151216/42545751_0.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u7761\u5728\u6211\u4e0a\u94fa\u7684\u5144\u5f1f\u300b\u5b9a\u68634\u67081\u65e5 \u70ed\u8840\u9752\u6625\u71c3\u503c\u7206\u8868|website=ifeng|date=December 16, 2015|language=zh}}</ref> In the same year Li co-starred alongside [[Zhang Ruoyun]] and [[Jiao Junyan]] in the crime medical web drama ''[[Medical Examiner Dr. Qin]]'' as the criminal police captain Lin Tao,<ref name=qin>{{cite web|url=http://ent.163.com/16/1018/12/C3LMKDV3000380EO.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u6cd5\u533b\u79e6\u660e\u300b\u83b7\u8d5e\u4e0b\u996d\u5267 \u674e\u73b0\"\u4e09\u526f\u8138\u5b54\"\u53cd\u5dee\u840c_\u7f51\u6613\u5a31\u4e50|website=Netease|date=October 18, 2016|language=zh}}</ref> which was acclaimed for both its storyline and performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/ent/2016/11/25/424878.html|script-title=zh:\u6f14\u5458\u65b0\u52bf\u529b\u4e28\u674e\u73b0\uff1a\u521a\u62cd\u300a\u6cd5\u533b\u79e6\u660e\u300b\uff0c\u8fd8\u633a\"\u5012\u80c3\u53e3\"\u7684|date=November 25, 2016|website=Beijing News|language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/culture/2016-12/14/content_27663593.htm|title=Behind the success of 'Medical Examiner Dr. Qin'|work=China Daily|date=December 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/1023044.shtml|title=Sohu TV drama \u2018Medical Examiner Dr. Qin\u2019 receives more than 1.2 billion views|work=Global Times|date=December 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he co-starred with [[Angelababy]], [[Jing Bairan]], and [[Bai Yu (actor)|Bai Yu]] in the romatic movie \"[[Love O2O (film)|Love O2O]]\", and played the roommate of the leading actor Xiao Nai, Yu Banshan in the film. In 2017, his web drama ''[[Tientsin Mystic]]'' which was broadcast internationally on [[Netflix]].<ref name=tien>{{cite web|url=https://news.china.com/news100/11038989/20170706/30927237.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u6cb3\u795e\u300b\u5b9a\u6863719 \"\u987d\u75de\u6cb3\u795e\"\u674e\u73b0\u8d64\u8eab\u79c0\u6c34\u6027|date=July 6, 2017|website=China.com|language=zh}}</ref> made him received a lot of praise for \"acting burst\", and also accumulated his first fans for him. The job offer he received was one year in a row, and in order to enter the role attentively, he refused other jobs during the filming.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201804/18/WS5ad68c6aa3105cdcf6518e5c.html|title=Dramatic improvement |website=China Daily|date=April 18, 2018}}</ref> and <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_1763753|script-title=zh:\u4e13\u8bbf\uff5c\u674e\u73b0\uff1a\u4e0d\u662f\u6211\u591a\u5e05\uff0c\u662f\u90ed\u5f97\u53cb\u5f88\u5e05|date=August 17, 2017|website=The Paper|language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.people.com.cn/n1/2017/0913/c86955-29532241.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u6cb3\u795e\u300b\u674e\u73b0\uff1a\u6f14\u597d\u6bcf\u4e2a\u89d2\u8272 \u4f53\u4f1a\u4e0d\u4e00\u6837\u7684\u4eba\u751f|date=September 13, 2017|website=People's Daily|language=zh}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, Li starred in the romance drama  ''[[Only Side by Side with You]]'' as a special forces agent.<ref name=side>{{cite web|url=http://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2017-04-07/doc-ifyecezv2449403.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a\u5357\u65b9\u6709\u4e54\u6728\u300b\u66dd\u9635\u5bb9 \u9648\u4f1f\u9706\u674e\u73b0\u4e0a\u6f14\u5236\u670d\u8bf1\u60d1|website=Sina|language=zh|date=April 7, 2017}}</ref> He starred in Australia's ''Explore Melbourne'' China campaign,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |first1=The |title=Australia Launches 'Explore Melbourne' Campaign Aimed at Chinese Tourists |url=https://brandinginasia.com/australia-launches-explore-melbourne-campaign-aimed-chinese-tourists/ |website=Branding in Asia Magazine |accessdate=2 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180314055947/https://brandinginasia.com/australia-launches-explore-melbourne-campaign-aimed-chinese-tourists/ |archivedate=March 14, 2018 |language=en |date=March 14, 2018}}</ref> as well as the Visit Victoria TV's commercial<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sun |first1=Herald |title=Visit Victoria wants to attract wealthy Chinese Millennials |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/visit-victoria-wants-to-attract-wealthy-chinese-millennials/news-story/918e8a2da3ae9e646959748e172b71dc |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Herald Sun]] |date=March 12, 2018 |quote=Actor Li Xian will front a Visit Victoria TV commercial aimed at enticing wealthy young Chinese Millennials to come to Melbourne}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u2013present: Breakthrough===\nIn 2019, Li starred in the romance comedy drama Go Go Squid! as a brooding esports champion, marked a breakthrough for him. Gained 20 million followers in 2019, as well as endorsement and awards<ref name=xian></ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Canaves |first1=Sky |title=CBI Case Study: Male Celebrities Give Beauty Marketing a Makeover |url=http://chinafilminsider.com/case-study-male-celebrities-beauty/ |website=China Film Insider |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en |date=15 October 2019 |quote=Li Xian\u2019s performance as a brooding esports champion on \u201cGo Go Squid!\u201d marked a breakthrough for the actor.}}</ref><ref name=squid>{{cite web|url=http://ent.163.com/18/0214/11/DAJQFEU5000380EN.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u871c\u6c41\u7096\u9c7f\u9c7c\u300b\u6768\u7d2b\u674e\u73b0\u840c\u59b9\u9047\u7537\u795e\u4e00\u89c1\u949f\u60c5|date=February 14, 2018|website=Netease|language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ent.huanqiu.com/movie/yingshi-neidi/2019-07/15095685.html?agt=15422|script-title=zh:\u300a\u4eb2\u7231\u7684\uff0c\u70ed\u7231\u7684\u300b\u5b9a\u68630709 \u6768\u7d2b\u674e\u73b0\u5f00\u542f\u70ed\u8840\u751c\u7231|date=July 5, 2019|website=Global Times|language=zh}}</ref> The same year, he starred in the wuxia drama ''[[Sword Dynasty]]'' produced by [[Feng Xiaogang]]. \n\nIn 2020, Li appeared in [[CCTV New Year's Gala]] for the first time, performing the song item \"Hello 2020\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=CGTN |title=2020 Spring Festival Gala unveils programs |url=https://news.cgtn.com/news/2020-01-23/2020-Spring-Festival-Gala-unveils-programs-NuxacNCF0Y/index.html |website=news.cgtn.com |publisher=CGTN |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en |date=January 23, 2020 |quote=As for the singing and dancing programs, a number of the most popular actors and singers have been invited to the gala, such as Li Xian,...}}</ref>with [[Zhu Yilong]], [[Li Qin (actress)|Li Qin]], [[Ma Sichun]] & [[Zhou Dongyu]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ent.sina.com.cn/v/m/2020-01-24/doc-iihnzhha4525233.shtml|title=\u9c9c\u8089\u9c9c\u82b1\u9f50\u540c\u6846 \u6731\u4e00\u9f99\u674e\u73b0\u8868\u767d2020|date=January 24, 2020|website=Sina|language=zh}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ent.sina.com.cn/tv/zy/2020-01-22/doc-iihnzahk5837362.shtml|title=\u674e\u73b0\u79f0\u9996\u6b21\u53c2\u52a0\u6625\u665a\u5f88\u60ca\u8bb6\uff1a\u6ca1\u7ecf\u5386\u8fc7 \u8fd8\u86ee\u7d27\u5f20\u7684|date=January 22, 2019|website=Sina|language=zh}}</ref> He starred in the film ''The Enigma of Arrival'', which premiered at the [[Busan International Film Festival]]. In March Li participated in a song to encourage citizens of Wuhan in their fight against [[COVID-19]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laura-Achim |first1=Adina |title=Should Chinese Idols And KOLs Try To Help Fight COVID-19? |url=https://jingdaily.com/should-chinese-idols-and-kols-try-to-help-fight-covid-19/ |website=Jing Daily |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en |date=March 18, 2020 |quote=Gem (\u5b9d\u77f3) recently launched a new song to encourage citizens of Wuhan in their fight against COVID-19, and idols Li Xian}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n===General===\n{{Quote box | width=30% | align=right| quote=Li Xian\u2019s popularity may fluctuate with time, but the values, beliefs, and aspirations he stands for \u2014 an entrepreneurial spirit, consideration for independent women, patriotism, fitness, authenticity, and discipline \u2014 will be around for a long time.|source=Dao Nguyen of ''[[Jing Daily]]'' in 2019<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nguyen |first1=Dao |title=China\u2019s Changing Masculinity Propels a Brand New Idol |url=https://jingdaily.com/chinas-changing-masculinity-propels-a-brand-new-idol/ |website=Jing Daily |accessdate=1 April 2020|language=en |date=October 22, 2019}}</ref> }}\nLi Xian was favored by the director for his handsome appearance and skillful acting skills. He has left everyone with the impression of sunshine, handsomeness and versatile healing department warm men (China Entertainment Network Review)   .\nLi belongs to the kind of simmering actor. From the forest team in Forensic Qin Ming to the Guo team in River God, Li Xian is just right on the tough and handsome role. Each of Li Xian's works has a good response. The characters he plays each time are also very characteristic and individual, and he also sees his unique vision. The \"sculpture-like\" figure, the hormonal breath, also reflects his self-discipline and strict requirements on himself (reviewed by Xinhua News, New Express, and Peninsula Metropolis Daily). Li's eyes can speak, and his eyes can pass on the character's soul. His performance is delicate and layered. He can capture people's hearts by his face value, but he is a \u201cnaughter\u201d with strong acting skills. In the face of different situations, his performance instantly switches like a chameleon. In front of the camera, it is either public or casual or erupts, showing natural aura (Review of The Peninsula Metropolis).\n\nLi has been labeled as \"July Boyfriend\" by netizen after his role as Han Sahangyan in Go Go Squid! He was often featured in [[fashion magazines]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=chinadailiy.com.cn |title=Actor Li Xian poses for fashion magazine - Chinadaily.com.cn |url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201909/14/WS5d8094dba310cf3e3556bf83.html |website=www.chinadaily.com.cn |accessdate=2 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191012092237/https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201909/14/WS5d8094dba310cf3e3556bf83.html |archivedate=October 12, 2019 |date=September 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Weibo===\nIn 2019, following the successful of his summer drama ''Go Go Squid!'' Li Xian followers on [[Microblogging in China|Weibo]] grew quickly from 5 million to 20 million.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Transcribers |first1=Motley Fool |title=Weibo Corporation (WB) Q3 2019 Earnings Call Transcript |url=https://www.fool.com/earnings/call-transcripts/2019/11/14/weibo-corporation-wb-q3-2019-earnings-call-transcr.aspx |website=The Motley Fool |accessdate=2 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115015810/https://www.fool.com/earnings/call-transcripts/2019/11/14/weibo-corporation-wb-q3-2019-earnings-call-transcr.aspx |archivedate=November 15, 2019 |language=en |date=November 14, 2019 |quote=This quarter a TV series called Go Go Squid! became very popular on Weibo as well as its leading actor Li Xian whose fan base grew quickly from 5 million to 20 million.}}</ref>\n\n==Endorsements==\nLi appointed as ambassador [[China Youth Development Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=TV |first1=London |title=Chinese Actor Li Xian and His Fans Playing an Unexpected Role against the Coronavirus |url=https://london-tv.co.uk/chinese-actor-li-xian-and-his-fans-playing-an-unexpected-role-against-the-coronavirus/ |website=London TV |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\nIn 2019 Li become the first brand ambassador of [[Atlantis Resorts|Atlantis Sanya]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanya |first1=Atlantis |title=Official Announcement! \u201cJuly Boyfriend\u201d Li Xian Officially Appointed As Brand Ambassador For Atlantis Sanya |url=https://www.accesswire.com/559785/Official-Announcement-July-Boyfriend-Li-Xian-Officially-Appointed-As-Brand-Ambassador-For-Atlantis-Sanya |website=www.accesswire.com/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=September 16, 2019 |quote=Atlantis Sanya officially announced actor Li Xian as the resort\u2019s first Brand Ambassador.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Atlantis Sanya Invited Li Xian to be its Brand Ambassador |url=https://www.accesswire.com/564055/Atlantis-Sanya-Invited-Li-Xian-to-be-its-Brand-Ambassador |website=www.accesswire.com |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en |date=October 24, 2020}}</ref>he also endorsed [[Honor (brand)|Honor]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Yordari |title=Honor 30 and 30 Pro arriving on April 15 |url=https://www.gsmarena.com/honor_30_series_officially_arriving_on_april_15-news-42343.php |website=GSMArena.com |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref> [[Est\u00e9e Lauder Companies|Est\u00e9e Lauder]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lavin |first1=Frank |title=How Does 12.12 Fit Into Your China Strategy? |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/franklavin/2019/12/12/how-does-1212-fit-into-your-china-strategy/#55fb1e6f3121 |website=Forbes |accessdate=1 April 2020 |language=en |date=December 12, 2019 |quote=Estee Lauder, as an example, produced an ad campaign using celebrities Li Xian and Yang Mi to promote its Aqua Brilliance line.}}</ref>, [[Midea_Group#Products|Midea]], [[JD.com]], [[Lay's]], [[Levi Strauss & Co.|Levi's]], [[Yili Group|Yili]], two beverage company, and an ice cream brand.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Li Xian filmography}}\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n;Film\n* ''[[Schemes in Antiques]]'' (2020) as Yao Buran\n* ''[[Love Song 1980]]'' (2020) as Zheng Wen\n* ''[[Chi Hu Shu Sheng]]'' (2020) as Bao Shisan\n* ''[[Leap (film)|Leap]]'' (2020, cameo)\n* ''[[The Enigma of Arrival]]'' (2020) as Xiao Long\n* ''[[The Captain (2019 film)|The Captain]]'' (2019, cameo)\n* ''[[Nuts (2018 film)|Nuts]] '' (2018) as Xu Zicong\n* ''[[The Founding of an Army]]'' (2017) as Luo Ruohang\n* ''[[Deadly Love]]'' (2017) as Fang Zhibin\n* ''[[Love O2O (film)|Love O2O]]'' (2016) as Yu Banshan\n* ''[[Who Sleeps My Bro]]'' (2016) as Xie Xun\n* ''[[Singing When We Are Young]]'' (2013) as Da Wei\n* ''[[Fengshui (2018 film)|Feng Shui]]'' (2012) as Ma Xiaobao\n\n{{col-2}}\n;Television\n* ''[[A Love Never Lost]]'' (2020)\n* ''[[Sword Dynasty]]'' (2019) as Ding Ning\n* ''[[Go Go Squid!]]'' (2019) as Han Shangyan\n* ''[[Women in Shanghai]]'' (2018) as Chen Xiaowei (Guest)\n* ''[[Only Side By Side With You]]'' (2018) as Cheng Jianxiong\n* ''[[Tientsin Mystic]]'' (2017) as Guo Deyou\n* ''[[Rush to the Dead Summer]]'' (2017) as Qing Yun (Cameo)\n* ''[[Medical Examiner Dr. Qin]]'' (2016) as Lin Tao\n* ''[[Who Sleeps My Bro]]'' (2016) as Xie Xun\n* ''[[Four Ladies]]'' (2016) as Ding Zihui\n* ''[[City of Fantasy]]'' (2014) as Ah Liang\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Others===\n====Short film====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! width=10|Year\n! English title\n! Chinese title \n! Role\n! Notes/Ref.\n|- \n| rowspan=2|2013 ||''12 Years'' || {{lang|zh|12\u5e74}} || Lin Xiaofeng || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.17173.com/content/2013-07-22/20130722155531452_all.shtml|script-title=zh:\u300a12\u5e74\u300b\u5fae\u7535\u5f71 \u4e00\u5982\u521d\u89c1\u76f8\u4f34\u6c38\u8fdc|date=July 22, 2013|language=zh}}</ref> \n|- \n|''Confess'' || {{lang|zh|\u8868\u767d}} || || \n|- \n|2016 || ''The Gift'' || {{lang|zh-Hans|\u661f\u9645\u793c\u7269}} || Wang Qi || <ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.yule.com.cn/html/201603/215328.html|script-title=zh:\u674e\u73b0\u79d1\u5e7b\u5fae\u7535\u5f71\u53d1\u5e03 \u6f14\u7ece\u661f\u9645\u7a7f\u8d8a\u4e4b\u7231|date=March 12, 2016|website=Yule|language=zh}}</ref>\n|- \n| 2018 || ''Explore Melbourne with Li Xian'' || {{lang|zh-Hans|\u58a8\u5c14\u672c \u6211\u672c\u7279\u7acb\u72ec\u884c}} ||  || Promotional film for Visit Victoria Campaign Launch Event |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://travel.sina.com.cn/outbound/news/2018-03-13/detail-ifyscsmv1764467.shtml|script-title=zh:\u7ef4\u591a\u5229\u4e9a\u5dde\u65c5\u6e38\u5c40\u53d1\u5e03\u4e2d\u56fd\u533a\u54c1\u724c\uff1a\u58a8\u5c14\u672c\uff0c\u6211\u672c\u7279\u7acb\u72ec\u884c|date=March 13, 2019|website=Sina|language=zh}}</ref>\n|- \n|}\n\n====Music video====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! width=10|Year\n! English title\n! Ch