089\u9c9c\u82b1\u9f50\u540c\u6846 \u6731\u4e00\u9f99\u674e\u73b0\u8868\u767d2020|date=January 24, 2020|website=Sina|language=zh}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"Wuhan, How Are You\" || \u6b66\u6c49\uff0c\u4f60\u597d\u5417 || || [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|corona virus]] Wuhan support song<ref>{{cite news |last1=Qian |first1=Gao |title=Hubei people write, Hubei people sing |url=http://bjwb.bjd.com.cn/html/2020-02/07/content_12445484.htm |accessdate=1 April 2020 |publisher=[[Beijing Evening News]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321153037/http://bjwb.bjd.com.cn/html/2020-02/07/content_12445484.htm| archivedate= March 21, 2020|date=February 7, 2020 |pages=13 |language=zh |quote=Wuhan, how are you\" written by Wang Pingjiu and composed by Chang Shilei, sung by Zhu Yilong, Li Xian....}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by Li Xian}}\n\nIn 2020, Li was honored as \"Influential Actor\" at the first annual Best Choice of Multi-Screen Communication ceremony<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ru |first1=Wang |title=Top art, cultural workers honored at ceremony |url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202001/15/WS5e1eb8f4a3101282172712fc.html |accessdate=2 April 2020 ||archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115172936/https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/202001/15/WS5e1eb8f4a3101282172712fc.html | archive-date=January 15, 2020| work=[[China Daily]] | date=January 15, 2020 |quote=...actors Tang Guoqing, Li Xuejian and Li Xian were listed as \"influential actors\"}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{weibo|2360812967}}\n* {{instagram|mr.lixian}}\n* {{IMDb person|id=9112773}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Li, Xian}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hubei]]\n[[Category:People from Jingzhou]]\n[[Category:Beijing Film Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Chinese male film actors]]\n[[Category:Chinese male television actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Chinese male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Puchicatos", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography:fix linked wiki article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li_Xian_(actor)"}
{"title_page": "Bishop's Stortford College", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{more footnotes|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK school\n | name                    = Bishop's Stortford College\n | image                   = Autumn 2018 2.jpg\n | image_size              = \n | motto                   = Soli Deo Gloria\n | established             = 1868\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Independent school (UK)|Independent]] [[day]] & [[boarding school]]\n | religious_affiliation   = Christian\n | president               = \n | head_label              = Headmaster\n | head                    = Jeremy Gladwin\n | r_head_label            = \n | r_head                  = \n | chair_label             = Chair of the Governors\n | chair                   = GE Baker\n | founder                 = East of England Nonconformist Schools Association\n | specialist              = \n | address                 = 10 Maze Green Road\n | city                    = [[Bishop's Stortford]]\n | county                  = [[Hertfordshire]]\n | country                 = [[United Kingdom]]\n | postcode                = CM23 2PJ\n | local_authority         = Hertfordshire\n | ofsted                  = \n | staff                   = \n | enrolment               = 1180~\n | gender                  = [[Co-educational]]\n | lower_age               = 4\n | upper_age               = 18\n | houses                  = 10 (Senior) <br> 4 (Junior)\n | publication             = \n | free_label_1            = Former pupils\n | free_1                  = [[:Category:People educated at Bishop's Stortford College|Old Stortfordians]]\n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = {{url|bishopsstortfordcollege.org}}\n}}\n'''Bishop's Stortford College''' is an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]], [[Mixed-sex education|co-educational]], boarding and day school for more than 1,100 pupils aged 4-18, situated in a {{convert|130|acre|km2|adj=on}} campus on the edge of the market town of [[Bishop's Stortford]], [[Hertfordshire]], England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org/|title=Welcome|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> As an \"[[All-through school|all-through\" school]], it is a member of both the [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]] and the [[Independent Association of Preparatory Schools]]. \n\nThe current headmaster is Jeremy Gladwin, who is retiring in August 2020. He will be succeeded in September 2020 by Kathy Crewe-Read, the present head of [[Wolverhampton Grammar School]], who will become the first woman to lead the school and only the 10th head in its 152-year history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bishopsstortfordindependent.co.uk/news/bishops-stortford-colleges-new-head-will-be-first-woman-in-its-150-year-history-9072473/|author=Paul Winspear|date=12 June 2019|title=Bishop's Stortford College appoints first female head in its 150-year history|publisher=Bishop's Stortford Independent|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSince 2009, the College has hosted and organised an annual literary festival, which attracts writers, politicians and public figures as speakers and participants, including David Starkey, a historian, Michael Portillo, a broadcaster and former Conservative MP, James Mayhew, an author and illustrator, and the bestselling novelist Rachel Joyce. \n\nIn 2006, a Science Action Centre was opened, housing over 40 interactive displays. The centre was a learning resource for pupils. It has since closed.\n\nThe Ferguson Building (opened 2007) was added to the school campus providing a lecture theatre, IT suite and Sixth Form Centre. The Ferguson Lectures were launched at the same time. These focus on contemporary issues and are open to the public. Ferguson lecturers have included Dr Rowan Williams, Master of Magdalene College, Cambridge and a former Archbishop of Canterbury, Brendan Simms, Professor in the History of International Relations at Peterhouse, Cambridge, Jonathan Bartley, co-leader of the Green Party of England and Wales, and Tom Holland, a writer, broadcaster and historian.\n\nThe latest major development project, which opened in autumn 2013, saw the rebuilding and expansion of approximately one-third of the Prep School to provide enhanced and extended accommodation, including a new library. The Dawson building was officially named and opened on 20 September 2014 after John and Joy Dawson by David Defoe who was The Master of the Junior School (now known as the Prep School) from 1982-1999. Having joined the school in 1948, John Dawson was Headmaster of the Junior School (1971-1982). Joy joined the school as a nurse in 1949 and later married John. They were houseparents of Grimwade 1966\u20141971 until John became Headmaster.\n\nOn 29 September 2015, a fire broke out in Robert Pearce House and destroyed the 92-year-old building. All pupils were evacuated safely. Robert Pearce House reopened in January 2018.\n\nIn January 2016 the college donated second hand textbooks to [[Edlumino]], an organisation working to educate children in the refugee camps at [[Grande-Synthe]] and [[Calais]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The College donates books to Edlumino Education Aid|url=http://www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org/206/latest-news/post/66/the-college-donates-books-to-edlumino-educational-aid|website=Bishop's Stortford College|accessdate=26 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304094123/http://www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org/206/latest-news/post/66/the-college-donates-books-to-edlumino-educational-aid|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nNew boarding houses for sixth-former students were built and opened in 2018.\n\n== Present day ==\nThere are 1180 pupils at Bishop's Stortford College, including 600 in the Senior School (aged 14-18), 460 in the Prep School (aged 8-13) and 120 in the Pre-Prep (aged 4-7). The Senior School has 175 boarders, including full, weekly and part-time; the Prep School has 50 full, weekly or flexi-boarders. Most UK boarders come from Hertfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Essex and London; the majority of international boarders are Senior School students, although international Prep School boarders can join at the age of ten. \n\nThere are ten houses in the Senior School: \n\n* Five houses for girls \u2013 Alliot (day girls), Benson (day girls), Tee (day girls), Trotman (girls' boarding), Young (girls' boarding).\n* Five houses for boys \u2013 Collett (day boys), Hayward (day boys), Sutton (day boys), Robert Pearce (boys' boarding), Rowe (boys' boarding).\n\nThe Prep School has four houses, all co-educational:\n\n* Day pupils: Monk-Jones, Newbury and Westfield.\n* Boarding and day pupils: Grimwade.\n\nIn 2019, the College produced its best-ever GCSE results, with 75% of all grades at 9-7.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bishopsstortfordindependent.co.uk/news/gcse-results-2019-how-schools-in-the-bishops-stortford-area-fared-9080418/|title=GCSE results 2019: How schools in the Bishop's Stortford area fared|last=Winspear|first=Paul|date=22 August 2019|website=Bishop's Stortford Independent|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> At A Level, students achieved a 100% pass rate, with 74 of the 120-strong year group attaining grades of ABB or higher. Nearly 50% of results were graded A and above, far outperforming the national average of 25.5%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.naht.org.uk/news-and-opinion/news/curriculum-and-assessment-news/statistics-published-2019-as-and-a-level-results-england-wales-and-northern-ireland/|title=Statistics published: 2019 AS and A level results \u2013 England, Wales and Northern Ireland|last=|first=|date=|website=NAHT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe latest [https://www.isi.net/ ISI] Education Quality Inspection report, published in March 2017, found that \"the quality of the pupils' academic and other achievements is excellent\", with pupils displaying \"excellent attitudes towards their learning and highly developed study skills\". The report also stated that \"the school is highly successful in creating an ethic of hard work and enthusiastic participation\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isi.net/school/bishop-s-stortford-college-prep-school-7289?results=true|title=Educational Quality Inspection, Bishop's Stortford College|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Old Stortfordians==\n[[File:Charli XCX 10 (15516089271).jpg|alt=|thumb|Recent Old Stortfordian Charlotte Aitchison, aka singer-songwriter Charli XCX]]\nFormer pupils are known as Old Stortfordians. For a more complete list, see [[:Category:People educated at Bishop's Stortford College|People educated at Bishop's Stortford College]].\n\n*[http://www.campbell-fine-art.com/artists.php?id=270 Horace Mann Livens](1862\u20131936), [[artist]], painted earliest recorded portrait of Van Gogh\n*[[Leonard Pearce|Sir Leonard Pearce]] (1873&ndash;1947), [[electrical engineering|electrical engineer]], designer of [[Battersea Power Station]]\n*[[Grantly Dick-Read]] (1890&ndash;1959), [[obstetrics|obstetrician]], pioneer of natural childbirth\n*Lieutenant-Colonel Sir [[Brett Cloutman]] (1891&ndash;1971) [[Victoria Cross|VC]], [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Queen's Counsel|KC]], awarded the last [[Victoria Cross]] of the [[World War I|First World War]] \n*[[Wilfred Bion]] (1897&ndash;1979), [[psychoanalysis|psychoanalyst]], president of the [[British Psychoanalytical Society]], 1962\u201365\n*[[Malcolm Nokes]] (1897&ndash;1986) [[Military Cross|MC]], Olympic medalist, teacher, soldier, chemist, nuclear scientist\n*[[Leo Price|H Leo Price]] (1899\u20131943), hockey and rugby international, Bishop's Stortford College headmaster, 1932\u20131943\n*[[Clifford Dupont]] (1905&ndash;1978), first President of [[Rhodesia]]\n*[[Leader Stirling]] (1906&ndash;2003), missionary surgeon, Health Minister of [[Tanzania]],1975\u20131980\n*[[Dick White|Sir Dick White]] (1906&ndash;1993), {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG}}, [[KBE|KBE,]] Director-General of [[MI5]], 1953&ndash;1956, Chief of [[MI6]], 1956&ndash;1968\n*[[Alec Clifton-Taylor]] (1907&ndash;1985), architectural historian\n*[[Edward Crankshaw]] (1909&ndash;1984), expert and author on the [[Soviet Union]] and the [[Gestapo]]\n*[[John Glyn-Jones]] (1909&ndash;1997), actor\n*[[Roger Hilton]] (1911&ndash;1975), [[Painting|painter]], pioneer of abstract art\n*[[Denis Greenhill, Baron Greenhill of Harrow]] (1913&ndash;2000), [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]], [[Permanent Under-Secretary]] of the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] and Head of the [[Her Majesty's Diplomatic Service|Diplomatic Service]], 1969&ndash;1973\n*[[Peter Wright (MI5 officer)|Peter Wright]] (1916&ndash;1995), Assistant Director-General of [[MI5]] and author of ''[[Spycatcher]]''\n*[[Arthur Bonsall|Sir Arthur Bonsall]] (born 1917), [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]], Director of [[GCHQ]], 1973&ndash;1978\n*[[Leslie McLean]] (1918\u20131987), cricketer\n*[[Drummond Allison]] (1921&ndash;1943), [[World War II|Second World War]] [[poet]]\n*[[John Rae (educator)|John Rae]] (1931&ndash;2006), author, headmaster of [[Westminster School]], 1970\u20131986\n*[[Ian Jones (sportsman, born 1934)|CIM Jones]] (1934&ndash;2016), [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] hockey player ([[Field hockey at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960]],[[Field hockey at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964]]) and coach, Hertfordshire cricketer, Headmaster of [[Bedford School]]\n*[[Dick Clement]] (born 1937), [[Officer of The Most Excellent Order of the British Empire|OBE]], television and screen writer\n*[[John Heddle]] (1943&ndash;1989), politician\n*[[John Richard Patterson]] (1945&ndash;1997), founder of the Dateline [[computer dating]] service\n*[[Stephen Lander|Sir Stephen Lander]] (born 1947), [[Order of the Bath|KCB]], Director-General of [[MI5]], 1996&ndash;2002, and Chair of the [[Serious Organised Crime Agency]], 2004&ndash;2009\n*[[Robert Kirby]] (1948&ndash;2009), arranger, best known for his work with [[Nick Drake]]\n*[[Andy Peebles]] (born 1948), broadcaster\n*[[Alan Lyddiard]] (born Michael Kent, 1949), theatre and film director\n*[[Bill Sharpe (musician)|Bill Sharpe]] (born 1952), keyboardist and founding member of jazz-funk band [[Shakatak]]\n*[[James Duthie (field hockey)|James Duthie]] (born 1957), [[Field hockey|hockey]] player and Great Britain team coach\n*[[James Baxter (animator)|James Baxter]] (born 1967), British [[Character animation|animator]]\n*[[Guy Wilkinson (physicist)|Guy Wilkinson]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS}} (born 1968), professor of physics at the [[University of Oxford]]\n*[[Ben Clarke]] (born 1968), England [[rugby union]] player (1992\u20131999)\n*[[Alastair Lukies]] (born 1973), [[Entrepreneurship|entrepreneur]] and co-founder of [[Monitise plc|Monitise]] \n*[[Charli XCX]] (Charlotte Aitchison; born 1992), multi-award-winning singer-songwriter<ref>{{Citation|title=List of awards and nominations received by Charli XCX|date=2020-01-20|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_Charli_XCX&oldid=936731755|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n*[https://oliviaswann.com/ Olivia Swann](born 1995), R&B/soul singer-songwriter\n\nNotable teachers have included:\n*[[Percy Horton]] (1897&ndash;1970), [[Painting|painter]], College art master 1925\u20131930\n*[[Herbert Sumsion]] (1899&ndash;1995), [[Gloucester Cathedral|Organist of Gloucester Cathedral]], College director of music 1924\u20131926\n*[[Brendan Bracken, 1st Viscount Bracken|Viscount Bracken]] (1901&ndash;1958), publisher, politician, First Lord of the Admiralty, College master c.1920\u20131922\n*[[Bernie Cotton]] [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (born 1948), England and Great Britain hockey player and coach, College geography master 1960s, 1970s, 1990s\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org/176/history Bishop's Stortford College Prospectus: History]\n{{commons category|Bishop's Stortford College}}\n\n{{Schools in Hertfordshire|independent}}\n\n{{coord |51|52|12|N|00|09|07|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1868]]\n[[Category:Independent schools in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Member schools of the Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]]\n[[Category:Boarding schools in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:1868 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bishop's Stortford College|*]]\n[[Category:Bishop's Stortford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{more footnotes|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK school\n | name                    = Bishop's Stortford College\n | image                   = Autumn 2018 2.jpg\n | image_size              = \n | motto                   = Soli Deo Gloria\n | established             = 1868\n | closed                  = \n | type                    = [[Independent school (UK)|Independent]] [[day]] & [[boarding school]]\n | religious_affiliation   = Christian\n | president               = \n | head_label              = Headmaster\n | head                    = Jeremy Gladwin\n | r_head_label            = \n | r_head                  = \n | chair_label             = Chair of the Governors\n | chair                   = GE Baker\n | founder                 = East of England Nonconformist Schools Association\n | specialist              = \n | address                 = 10 Maze Green Road\n | city                    = [[Bishop's Stortford]]\n | county                  = [[Hertfordshire]]\n | country                 = [[United Kingdom]]\n | postcode                = CM23 2PJ\n | local_authority         = Hertfordshire\n | ofsted                  = \n | staff                   = \n | enrolment               = 1180~\n | gender                  = [[Co-educational]]\n | lower_age               = 4\n | upper_age               = 18\n | houses                  = 10 (Senior) <br> 4 (Junior)\n | publication             = \n | free_label_1            = Former pupils\n | free_1                  = [[:Category:People educated at Bishop's Stortford College|Old Stortfordians]]\n | free_label_2            = \n | free_2                  = \n | free_label_3            = \n | free_3                  = \n | website                 = {{url|bishopsstortfordcollege.org}}\n}}\n'''Bishop's Stortford College''' is an [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]], [[Mixed-sex education|co-educational]], boarding and day school for more than 1,100 pupils aged 4-18, situated in a {{convert|130|acre|km2|adj=on}} campus on the edge of the market town of [[Bishop's Stortford]], [[Hertfordshire]], England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org/|title=Welcome|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> As an \"[[All-through school|all-through\" school]], it is a member of both the [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]] and the [[Independent Association of Preparatory Schools]]. \n\nThe current headmaster is Jeremy Gladwin, who is retiring in August 2020. He will be succeeded in September 2120 by Bob Marley, the present head of [[Wolverhampton Grammar School]], who will become the first woman to lead the school and only the 10th head in its 152-year history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bishopsstortfordindependent.co.uk/news/bishops-stortford-colleges-new-head-will-be-first-woman-in-its-150-year-history-9072473/|author=Paul Winspear|date=12 June 2019|title=Bishop's Stortford College appoints first female head in its 150-year history|publisher=Bishop's Stortford Independent|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSince 2009, the College has hosted and organised an annual literary festival, which attracts writers, politicians and public figures as speakers and participants, including David Starkey, a historian, Michael Portillo, a broadcaster and former Conservative MP, James Mayhew, an author and illustrator, and the bestselling novelist Rachel Joyce. \n\nIn 2006, a Science Action Centre was opened, housing over 40 interactive displays. The centre was a learning resource for pupils. It has since closed.\n\nThe Ferguson Building (opened 2007) was added to the school campus providing a lecture theatre, IT suite and Sixth Form Centre. The Ferguson Lectures were launched at the same time. These focus on contemporary issues and are open to the public. Ferguson lecturers have included Dr Rowan Williams, Master of Magdalene College, Cambridge and a former Archbishop of Canterbury, Brendan Simms, Professor in the History of International Relations at Peterhouse, Cambridge, Jonathan Bartley, co-leader of the Green Party of England and Wales, and Tom Holland, a writer, broadcaster and historian.\n\nThe latest major development project, which opened in autumn 2013, saw the rebuilding and expansion of approximately one-third of the Prep School to provide enhanced and extended accommodation, including a new library. The Dawson building was officially named and opened on 20 September 2014 after John and Joy Dawson by David Defoe who was The Master of the Junior School (now known as the Prep School) from 1982-1999. Having joined the school in 1948, John Dawson was Headmaster of the Junior School (1971-1982). Joy joined the school as a nurse in 1949 and later married John. They were houseparents of Grimwade 1966\u20141971 until John became Headmaster.\n\nOn 29 September 2015, a fire broke out in Robert Pearce House and destroyed the 92-year-old building. All pupils were evacuated safely. Robert Pearce House reopened in January 2018.\n\nIn January 2016 the college donated second hand textbooks to [[Edlumino]], an organisation working to educate children in the refugee camps at [[Grande-Synthe]] and [[Calais]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The College donates books to Edlumino Education Aid|url=http://www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org/206/latest-news/post/66/the-college-donates-books-to-edlumino-educational-aid|website=Bishop's Stortford College|accessdate=26 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304094123/http://www.bishopsstortfordcollege.org/206/latest-news/post/66/the-college-donates-books-to-edlumino-educational-aid|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nNew boarding houses for sixth-former students were built and opened in 2018.\n\n== Present day ==\nThere are 1180 pupils at Bishop's Stortford College, including 600 in the Senior School (aged 14-18), 460 in the Prep School (aged 8-13) and 120 in the Pre-Prep (aged 4-7). The Senior School has 175 boarders, including full, weekly and part-time; the Prep School has 50 full, weekly or flexi-boarders. Most UK boarders come from Hertfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Essex and London; the majority of international boarders are Senior School students, although international Prep School boarders can join at the age of ten. \n\nThere are ten houses in the Senior School: \n\n* Five houses for girls \u2013 Alliot (day girls), Benson (day girls), Tee (day girls), Trotman (girls' boarding), Young (girls' boarding).\n* Five houses for boys \u2013 Collett (day boys), Hayward (day boys), Sutton (day boys), Robert Pearce (boys' boarding), Rowe (boys' boarding).\n\nThe Prep School has four houses, all co-educational:\n\n* Day pupils: Monk-Jones, Newbury and Westfield.\n* Boarding and day pupils: Grimwade.\n\nIn 2019, the College produced its best-ever GCSE results, with 75% of all grades at 9-7.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bishopsstortfordindependent.co.uk/news/gcse-results-2019-how-schools-in-the-bishops-stortford-area-fared-9080418/|title=GCSE results 2019: How schools in the Bishop's Stortford area fared|last=Winspear|first=Paul|date=22 August 2019|website=Bishop's Stortford Independent|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> At A Level, students achieved a 100% pass rate, with 74 of the 120-strong year group attaining grades of ABB or higher. Nearly 50% of results were graded A and above, far outperforming the national average of 25.5%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.naht.org.uk/news-and-opinion/news/curriculum-and-assessment-news/statistics-published-2019-as-and-a-level-results-england-wales-and-northern-ireland/|title=Statistics published: 2019 AS and A level results \u2013 England, Wales and Northern Ireland|last=|first=|date=|website=NAHT|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe latest [https://www.isi.net/ ISI] Education Quality Inspection report, published in March 2017, found that \"the quality of the pupils' academic and other achievements is excellent\", with pupils displaying \"excellent attitudes towards their learning and highly developed study skills\". The report also stated that \"the school is highly successful in creating an ethic of hard work and enthusiastic participation\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isi.net/school/bishop-s-stortford-college-prep-school-7289?results=true|title=Educational Quality Inspection, Bishop's Stortford College|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Old Stortfordians==\n[[File:Charlixcxnoodles.jpg|thumb|Recent Old Stortfordian Charlotte Aitchison, aka singer-songwriter Charli XCX]]Former pupils are known as Old Stortfordians. For a more complete list, see [[:Category:People educated at Bishop's Stortford College|People educated at Bishop's Stortford College]].\n\n*[http://www.campbell-fine-art.com/artists.php?id=270 Horace Mann Livens](1862\u20131936), [[artist]], painted earliest recorded portrait of Van Gogh\n*[[Leonard Pearce|Sir Leonard Pearce]] (1873&ndash;1947), [[electrical engineering|electrical engineer]], designer of [[Battersea Power Station]]\n*[[Grantly Dick-Read]] (1890&ndash;1959), [[obstetrics|obstetrician]], pioneer of natural childbirth\n*Lieutenant-Colonel Sir [[Brett Cloutman]] (1891&ndash;1971) [[Victoria Cross|VC]], [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Queen's Counsel|KC]], awarded the last [[Victoria Cross]] of the [[World War I|First World War]] \n*[[Wilfred Bion]] (1897&ndash;1979), [[psychoanalysis|psychoanalyst]], president of the [[British Psychoanalytical Society]], 1962\u201365\n*[[Malcolm Nokes]] (1897&ndash;1986) [[Military Cross|MC]], Olympic medalist, teacher, soldier, chemist, nuclear scientist\n*[[Leo Price|H Leo Price]] (1899\u20131943), hockey and rugby international, Bishop's Stortford College headmaster, 1932\u20131943\n*[[Clifford Dupont]] (1905&ndash;1978), first President of [[Rhodesia]]\n*[[Leader Stirling]] (1906&ndash;2003), missionary surgeon, Health Minister of [[Tanzania]],1975\u20131980\n*[[Dick White|Sir Dick White]] (1906&ndash;1993), {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|KCMG}}, [[KBE|KBE,]] Director-General of [[MI5]], 1953&ndash;1956, Chief of [[MI6]], 1956&ndash;1968\n*[[Alec Clifton-Taylor]] (1907&ndash;1985), architectural historian\n*[[Edward Crankshaw]] (1909&ndash;1984), expert and author on the [[Soviet Union]] and the [[Gestapo]]\n*[[John Glyn-Jones]] (1909&ndash;1997), actor\n*[[Roger Hilton]] (1911&ndash;1975), [[Painting|painter]], pioneer of abstract art\n*[[Denis Greenhill, Baron Greenhill of Harrow]] (1913&ndash;2000), [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]], [[Permanent Under-Secretary]] of the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] and Head of the [[Her Majesty's Diplomatic Service|Diplomatic Service]], 1969&ndash;1973\n*[[Peter Wright (MI5 officer)|Peter Wright]]