{"title_page": "Angels in Islam", "text_new": "{{short description|Angels in Islamic tradition}}\n{{Islam |beliefs}}\n[[File:Islamic_angel,_persian_miniature.jpg|thumb|right|Angel in a [[Mughal miniature]], in the style of [[Bukhara]], 16th century]]\n[[File:'Angel Blowing a Woodwind', ink and opaque watercolor painting from Iran, c. 1500, Honolulu Academy of Arts.JPG|thumb|right|Angel Blowing a Woodwind', ink and opaque watercolor painting from Iran, c. 1500, Honolulu Academy of Arts]]\n\nIn Islam, [[angels]] ([[Arabic]]: {{lang|ar|{{large|\u0645\u0644\u0643}}}} ''{{transl|ar|DIN|malak}}''; plural: \u0645\u0644\u0627\u064b\u0626\u0650\u0643\u0629 ''mal\u0101'ikah'')<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia|author=Webb, Gisela | year= 2006 | title=Angel|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02be\u0101n|editor=Jane Dammen McAuliffe|publisher=Brill| doi= 10.1163/1875-3922_q3_EQCOM_00010 }}{{subscription required}}</ref> are believed to be celestial beings, created from a luminous origin by [[God in Islam|God]]. They have different functions, including praising God in heavens, interacting with humans ordinary life, and carrying laws of nature. Islam acknowledges the concept of angels both as [[anthropomorphic]] and abstract.<ref name=\"burge angels1\">Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}}</ref> Belief in angels is one of the six [[Iman (concept)#The Six Articles of Faith|articles of faith]] in [[Islam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/islam/beliefs/beliefs.shtml|title=BBC - Religions - Islam: Basic articles of faith|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813005904/http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/islam/beliefs/beliefs.shtml|archive-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> The Quran is the principal source for the Islamic concept of angels, but more extensive features of angels appear in [[hadith]]s, [[Isra and Mi'raj|Mi'raj literature]], [[kalam|Islamic theology]] and [[Islamic philosophy]].<ref>Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}} p. 22-23</ref> The angels differ from other spiritual creatures in their attitude as creatures of virtue in contrast to impure [[shaitan|demon]]s and morally ambivalent [[jinn]].<ref>Amira El-Zein Islam, Arabs, and Intelligent World of the Jinn Syracuse University Press 2009 {{ISBN|9780815650706}} page 20 </ref>\n\n==Corporeal angels==\n===Creation===\nAngels are another kind of creature created by God, known to mankind, commonly dwelling in the heavenly spheres. Although the Quran does not mention the time when angels were created, they are generally considered as the first creation of God. According to [[Tabari]], the angels had been created on Wednesday,<ref>Tobias N\u00fcnlist ''D\u00e4monenglaube im Islam'' Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG, 2015 {{ISBN|978-3-110-33168-4}} p. 43 (German)</ref> while other creatures on the following days. Although not mentioned in the Quran,<ref>Jane Dammen McAuliffe Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02bc\u0101n Brill: VOlume 3, 2005 {{ISBN|9789004123564}} p. 45 </ref> angels are believed to be created from a luminous substance, repeatedly described as a form of light. The probably most famous [[hadith]] regarding their origin is reported in [[Sahih Muslim]]: \"The Angels were created out of light and the [[Jann (legendary creature)|Jann]] was created out of a mixture of fire and Adam was created out of what characterizes you.\"<ref>{{ cite web |title=\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0632\u0647\u062f \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0642\u0627\u0626\u0642 Book 55, Hadith 78. The Book of Zuhd and Softening of Hearts. (10) Chapter: Miscellaneous Ahadith(10) \u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0641\u0650\u064a \u0623\u064e\u062d\u064e\u0627\u062f\u0650\u064a\u062b\u064e \u0645\u064f\u062a\u064e\u0641\u064e\u0631\u0650\u0651\u0642\u064e\u0629\u064d |url=https://sunnah.com/muslim/55/78 |website=sunnah.com |accessdate=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page=100}}</ref> ''Nur'', the term used for the ''light'' from which the angels are created from, usually corresponds to the cold light of night or the light of the moon,<ref>Jane Dammen McAuliffe Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02bc\u0101n Brill: Volume 3, 2005 {{ISBN|9789004123564}} p. 45 </ref> contrasted to ''nar'', which corresponds to ''fire'' or the diurnal and solar light from which the angels of punishment are said to be created of.<ref>Jane Dammen McAuliffe Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02be\u0101n Volume 5 Georgetown University, Washington DC p. 118</ref> Dividing angels into two groups created from different types of light is also attested by Tabari,<ref name=tafsir-al-tabiri-241>{{cite book |url=https://islaambooks.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/the-commentary-on-the-quran-volume-i-tafsir-al-tabari.pdf |last1=al-Tabari |title=Tafsir al-Tabiri |publisher=Islaam Books |page=241 |accessdate=16 March 2019}}</ref> [[Abd al-Ghani al-Maqdisi]],<ref>{{cite book |first1=Hamilton Alexander Rosskeen |last1=Gibb |title=The Encyclopaedia of Islam: NED-SAM |publisher=Brill |date=1995 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Encyclopaedia_of_Islam_NED_SAM.html?id=OO4pAQAAMAAJ |page=94}}</ref> [[Al-Jili]]<ref>Awn, Peter J. (1983). Satan's Tragedy and Redemption: Ibl\u012bs in Sufi Psychology. Leiden, Germany: Brill Publishers. p. 182 {{ISBN|978-9004069060}}.</ref> and [[Al-Suyuti]].<ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page= 58}}</ref> Suyuti distinguishes in his work [[Al-Hay\u2019a as-samya fi l-hay\u2019a as-sunmya]] angels as created from \"fire that eats, but does not drink\" in opposition to [[Shaitan|devils]] created from \"fire that drinks, but does not eat\" which is also identified with the fire of the sun.<ref>ANTON M. HEINEN ISLAMIC COSMOLOGY A STUDY OF AS-SUYUTI\u2019S al-Hay\u2019a as-samya fi l-hay\u2019a as-sunmya with critical edition, translation, and commentary ANTON M. HEINEN BEIRUT 1982 p. 143</ref> Scholars also argued that there is no distinction between ''nur'' and ''nar'' at all. Although not his conclusion, Tabari argued that both can be seen as the same substance, since both pass into each other but refer to the same thing on different degrees.<ref>Gauvain, Richard (2013). Salafi Ritual Purity: In the Presence of God. Abingdon, England: Routledge. p. 73. {{ISBN|978-0710313560}} p. 302</ref> Asserting that both fire and light are actually the same but on different degrees can also be found by [[Zakariya al-Qazwini|Qazwini]] and Ibishi.<ref>Syrinx von Hees Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 270</ref><ref>{{cite book |first1=Seyyed Hossein |last=Nasr |title=Islamic Life and Thought |publisher=Routledge |date=2013 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Islamic_life_and_thought.html?id=_jkNAQAAMAAJ |isbn=978-1-134-53818-8 |page=135}}</ref> The lack of distinction between fire and light might be explained by the fact that both are closely related [[Morphology (linguistics)|morphologically]] and [[Phonetics|phonetically]].<ref>Mustafa \u00d6ZT\u00dcRK ''JOURNAL OF ISLAMIC RESEARCH'' Vol 2 No 2 December 200</ref> [[Al-Baydawi]] argued that ''light'' serves only as a [[proverb]], but fire and light refers actually to the same substance.<ref>Houtsma, M. Th. (1993). E.J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936, Band 5. BRILL. p. 191. {{ISBN|978-9-004-09791-9}} p. 191</ref> Apart from light, other traditions also mention exceptions about angels created from fire, ice or water.<ref>Fr. Edmund Teuma, O.F.M. Conv ''THE NATURE OF \"IBLI$H IN THE QUR'AN AS INTERPRETED BY THE COMMENTATORS'' p. 16</ref>\n\n=== Characteristics ===\nOne of the Islamic major characteristic is their lack of bodily desires; they never get tired, do not eat or drink and have no anger.<ref name=\"glasse 49 50\"/> As with other monotheistic religions, angels are characteristics of their purity and obedience to God.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page=140}}</ref> However, their constant loyalty, towards God, emphasized by some Quranic verses such as {{cite quran|16|49|s=ns|b=n}}, does not necessarily imply [[impeccability]],<ref name=\"houtsma 191\"/> and the motif of erring angels is also known to Islam.<ref>[[Christoph Auffarth]], [[Loren T. Stuckenbruck]] ''The Fall of the Angels'' BRILL 2004 {{ISBN|978-9-004-12668-8}} page 161</ref> Some scholars on the other hand, among [[Hasan of Basra]] as one of the first,<ref>Omar Hamdan ''Studien Zur Kanonisierung des Korantextes: al-\u1e24asan al-Ba\u1e63r\u012bs Beitr\u00e4ge Zur Geschichte des Korans'' Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2006 {{ISBN|978-3-447-05349-5}} page 292 (German)</ref> extend their loyalty towards God to assume general impeccability. Those who accept the possibility of erring angels, advocate that actually only the messengers among the angels are infallible,<ref>Fr. Edmund Teuma THE NATURE OF \"IBLI$H IN THE QUR'AN AS INTERPRETED BY THE COMMENTATORS University of Malta p. 15-16</ref> since the Quran also describes angels as being tested.<ref>http://www.dinimizislam.com/detay.asp?Aid=3563</ref> [[Al-Baydawi]] argued, that angels only remain impeccable if they do not fall. [[Ibn Arabi]] stated that angels may err in opposing Adam as a vice-regent and fixing on their way of worshipping God to the exclusion of other creatures.<ref>Sa'diyya Shaikh ''Sufi Narratives of Intimacy: Ibn Arabi, Gender, and Sexuality'' Univ of North Carolina Press 2012 {{ISBN|978-0-807-83533-3}} page 114</ref><ref>Christian Krokus ''The Theology of Louis Massignon'' CUA Press 2017 {{ISBN|978-0-813-22946-1}} page 89</ref>\n\nAngels are usually described in [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic forms]] combined with supernatural images, such as wings, being of great size, wearing heavenly clothes and great beauty.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page=99}}</ref> Some angels are identified with specific colors, often with white, but some special angels have a distinct color, such as Gabriel being associated with the color green.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page=113}}</ref>\n\nScholars debated whether human or angels rank higher. The prostration of angels before [[Adam in Islam|Adam]] is often seen as evidence for humans' supremacy over angels. Nevertheless, other hold angels to be superior, as being free from  material deficits, such as anger and lust, Angels are free from such inferior urges and therefore superior, a position especially found among [[Mu'tazilites]] and some [[Asharites]].<ref name=\"houtsma 191\">{{cite book |first1=M. Th. |last1=Houtsma |title=E.J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936, Band 5 |publisher=BRILL |date=1993 \n |isbn=978-9-004-09791-9 |page=191}}</ref> A similar opinion was asserted by Hasan of Basri, who argued that angels are superior to humans due to their infallibility, originally opposed by both [[Sunnism|Sunnis]] and [[Shia]]s.<ref>Omar Hamdan Studien Zur Kanonisierung des Korantextes: al-\u1e24asan al-Ba\u1e63r\u012bs Beitr\u00e4ge Zur Geschichte des Korans Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2006 {{ISBN|978-3-447-05349-5}} page 293 (German)</ref> This view is based on the assumption of superiority of pure spirit against body and flesh. Contrarily argued, humans rank above angels, since for a human it is harder to be obedient and to worship God, hassling with bodily temptations, in contrast to angels, whose life is much easier and therefore their obedience is rather insignificant. Islam acknowledges a famous story about competing angels and humans in the tale of [[Harut and Marut]], who were tested to determine, whether or not, angels would do better than humans under the same circumstances,<ref>Patricia Crone THE BOOK OF WATCHERS IN THE QUR\u00c5N page 11</ref> a tradition opposed by later scholars, such as [[ibn Taimiyya]], but still accepted by earlier scholars, such as [[ibn Hanbal]].<ref>Reynolds, Gabriel Said, \u201cAngels\u201d, in: Encyclopaedia of Islam, THREE, Edited by: Kate Fleet, Gudrun Kr\u00e4mer, Denis Matringe, John Nawas, Everett Rowson. Consulted online on 16 October 2019 <http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/1573-3912_ei3_COM_23204> Erste Online-Erscheinung: 2009 Erste Druckedition: 9789004181304, 2009, 2009-3</ref> Some [[Sufism|Sufi traditions]] argue that a human generally ranks below angels, but developed to [[Al-Ins\u0101n al-K\u0101mil]], he ranks above angels.<ref>Mohamed Haj Yousef The Single Monad Model of the Cosmos: Ibn Arabi's Concept of Time and Creation ibnalarabi 2014 {{ISBN|978-1-499-77984-4}} page 292</ref> Comparable to another major opinion, that prophets and messengers among humans rank above angels, but the ordinary human below an angel, while the messengers among angels rank higher than prophets.<ref name=\"houtsma 191\"/> [[Maturidism]] generally holds that angels' and prophets' superiority and obedience derive from their virtues and insights to God's action, but not as their original purity.<ref>Ulrich Rudolph Al-M\u0101tur\u012bd\u012b und Die Sunnitische Theologie in Samarkand BRILL, 1997 {{ISBN|9789004100237}} pp. 54-56</ref>\n\n=== Purity ===\nAngels believed to be engaged in human affairs are closely related to Islamic purity and modesty rituals. Many [[hadith]]s, including [[Muwatta Imam Malik]] from one of the [[Kutub al-Sittah]], talk about angels being repelled by humans' state of impurity.<ref>Burge, S. R. \u201cImpurity / Danger!\u201d Islamic Law and Society, vol. 17, no. 3-4, 2010, pp. 320\u2013349. JSTOR, https://www.jstor.org/stable/23034917.p. 323</ref> Such angels keep a distance from humans, who polluted themselves by certain actions (such as sexual intercourse). However, angels might return to an individual as soon as the person (ritually) purified himself or herself. The absence of angels may cause several problems for the person. If driven away by ritual impurity, the [[Kiraman Katibin]], who record people's actions,<ref>Burge, S. R. \u201cImpurity / Danger!\u201d Islamic Law and Society, vol. 17, no. 3-4, 2010, pp. 320\u2013349. JSTOR, https://www.jstor.org/stable/23034917.p. 325</ref> and the [[Guardian angel]],<ref>Burge, S. R. \u201cImpurity / Danger!\u201d Islamic Law and Society, vol. 17, no. 3-4, 2010, pp. 320\u2013349. JSTOR, https://www.jstor.org/stable/23034917.p. 327</ref> will not perform their tasks assigned to the individual. Another hadith specifies, during the state of impurity, bad actions are still written down, but good actions are not. When a person tells a lie, angels nearly are separated from the person from the stench it emanates.<ref>Burge, S. R. \u201cImpurity / Danger!\u201d Islamic Law and Society, vol. 17, no. 3-4, 2010, pp. 320\u2013349. JSTOR, https://www.jstor.org/stable/23034917.328</ref> Angels also depart from humans when they are naked or are having a bath out of decency, but also curse people who are nude in public.\n\n== Abstract angels ==\n=== Philosophy ===\nIn Islamic philosophy, angels appear frequently as incorporeal creatures. [[Al-Kindi]] and [[Ibn Sina]] both define angels as simple substances, which means, they belong to the [[Celestial spheres]] comparable to [[Ptolemaic astronomy]], endowed with life, reason, and immortality, in contrast to sublunary entities such as humans and animals, who are endowed with life, and the former also with reason, but are mortal.<ref>Seyyed Hossein Nasr ''An Introduction to Islamic Cosmological Doctrines'' SUNY Press, 01.01.1993 {{ISBN|9780791415153}} p. 236</ref><ref>Syrinx von Hees Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 268 (German)</ref> Similar Qazwini assigns the angels to heavenly spheres, distinguishing them from among the animals, although both are said to possess the attribute of life. Significantly, [[Al-Damiri]] includes in his [[zoology|zoological]] works, animals, humans, [[jinn]] and even demons, but not angels.<ref>Houtsma, M. Th. (1993). E.J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936, Band 5. BRILL. p. 191. {{ISBN|978-9-004-09791-9}} p. 192</ref> Such cosmological thought, maintained by scholars such as [[Al-Farabi]] and Ibn Sina, has strong resemblance with the [[Neoplatonism|Neo-Platonistic]] [[Emanationism|emanation cosmology]], identifying the different angels in Islam with [[Nous|intellects]], dividing the cosmos into different spheres. However, Islamic scholars repeatedly insist that all heavenly spheres as a whole form a single body and are moved by God, in contrast to Aristotelian cosmology in which God only moves the outer sphere.<ref>Seyyed Hossein Nasr ''An Introduction to Islamic Cosmological Doctrines'' SUNY Press, 01.01.1993 {{ISBN|9780791415153}} p. 236</ref> According to ibn Sina, but differing from Al-Farabi, God is not part of the scheme of emanation. God emanated things in accordance with his will. In his ''Theologia Aristotelis'' he shows that through the manifestation of God, the intellects are aware of God and their role in the universe. Further Ibn Sina seems to distinguishes between two types of angels: One completely unrelated to matter, and another one, which exists in form of a superior kind of matter. The latter ones can carry messages between the heavenly spheres and the sublunary world, appearing in visions. Therefore, the higher angels dwell in [[Jabarut|higher spheres]], while their subordinate angels appear in an [[Malakut|intermediary realm]]. Ibn Sina's explanation might imply an attempt to consider revelation as part of the natural world.<ref name=\"glasse 49 50\">Cyril Glass\u00e9, Huston Smith, The New Encyclopedia of Islam Rowman Altamira 2003 {{ISBN|978-0-759-10190-6}} page 49-50</ref><ref>Abd Al-Jabbar, Ibn Sina and Al-Ghazali ''God and Humans in Islamic Thought'' Routledge 2006 {{ISBN|9780203965375}}  p. 97</ref> Also Qazwini lists a lower type of angels; earthly angels as indwelling forces of nature, who keep the world in order and never deviate from their duty. Qazwini believed that the existence of these angels could be proved by reason and effects of these angels on their assigned object.<ref>Syrinx von Hees Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 263</ref>\n\n=== Psychology ===\n{{Expand section | date=August 2019}}\nIslamic philosophy stressed that humans own angelic and demonic qualities and that the human soul is seen as a ''potential angel'' or ''potential [[Shaitan|demon]]''.<ref>Amira El-Zein Islam, Arabs, and Intelligent World of the Jinn Syracuse University Press 2009 {{ISBN|978-0-815-65070-6}} page 43</ref> Depending on whether the [[nafs|sensual soul]] or the [[Ruh|rational soul]] develop, the human soul becomes an angel or a demon.<ref>Khaled El-Rouayheb, Sabine Schmidtke The Oxford Handbook of Islamic Philosophy Oxford University Press 2016 {{ISBN|978-0-199-91739-6}} page 186</ref> Angels may also give inspirations opposite to the evil suggestions, called ''wasw\u0101s'', from [[Satan]].<ref name=\"thoughtco1\">https://www.thoughtco.com/angels-in-islam-2004030</ref>\n\n== In Ibn Abbas Mi'raj narrative ==\n[[File:Maalik_opens_the_gates_of_hell.jpg|thumb|Muhammad requests Maalik to show him Hell during his heavenly journey. Miniature from [[The David Collection]].]]\n[[File:Muhammad_encountering_the_angel_of_fire_and_ice.jpg|thumb|Muhammad encounters the Angel composed of fire and ice during his [[Isra and Mi'raj|Night journey]]. Miniature from a copy of al-Sarai\u2019s ''Nahj al-Faradis'' from [[The David Collection]]]]\n\n[[Muhammad]]'s encounter with several significant angels on his [[Isra and Mi'raj|journey through the celestial spheres]], play a major role in [[Ibn Abbas]] version.<ref>Hajjah Amina Adil (2012). \"Ezra\". ''Muhammad the Messenger of Islam: His life & prophecy''. BookBaby. {{ISBN|978-1-618-42913-1}}.</ref><ref>name=\"State University of New York Press\">{{cite book|last1=Colby|first1=Frederick S|title=Narrating Muhammad's Night Journey: Tracing the Development of the Ibn 'Abbas Ascension Discourse|date=2008|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-7518-8}}</ref> Many scholars such as [[Al-Tha`labi]] drew their exegesis upon this narrative, however it never led to an established angelology as known in Christianity.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! first heaven !! second heaven !! third heaven !! fourth heaven !! fifth heaven !! sixth heaven !! seventh heaven\n|-\n| [[Ishim (angel)|Habib]] || [[Azrael|Angel of Death]] || [[Maalik]] || Salsa'il || [[Kalqa'il]] || [[Michael (archangel)|Mikha'il]] (Archangel) || [[Israfil]]\n|-\n| Rooster angel || [[N\u0101zi'\u0101t and N\u0101shi\u1e6d\u0101t|Angels of death]] || Angel with seventy heads || Angels of the sun || - || [[Cherub]]im || [[Bearers of the Throne]]\n|-\n| [[Ri\u1e0dwan|Ismail (or ''Ri\u1e0dwan'')]] || Mika'il || Arina'il || - || - || Shamka'il || Afra'il\n|}\n\n==Individual angels==\nIslam has no standard hierarchical organization that parallels the [[Christian angelic hierarchy|division into different \"choirs\" or spheres]] hypothesized and drafted by early medieval [[Christian theology|Christian theologians]], but does distinguish between archangels and angels. Angels are not equal in status and consequently, they are delegated different tasks to perform.\n\n===Archangels===\n* [[Holy Spirit (Islam)#As interpreted to refer to the Archangel Gabriel|Jibr\u0101'\u012bl/Jibr\u012bl/Jabr\u012bl]] ([[English language|English]]: [[Gabriel]]),<ref>Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}} chapter 3</ref> the angel of revelation. Jibra'il is the archangel responsible for revealing the Quran to  [[Muhammad]], verse by verse. Jibra'il is the angel who communicates with (all of) the prophets and also descends with the blessings of God during the night of [[Laylat al-Qadr]] (\"The Night of Divine Destiny (Fate)\"). Jibra'il is also acknowledged as a magnificent warrior in Islamic tradition, who led an army of angels into the [[Battle of Badr]] and fought against Iblis as he tempted Jesus (Isa).<ref>Islam Issa ''Milton in the Arab-Muslim World'' Taylor & Francis 2016 {{ISBN|978-1-317-09592-7}} page 111</ref>\n* [[Michael (archangel)|M\u012bk\u0101l/M\u012bk\u0101\u02be\u012bl/M\u012bkh\u0101'\u012bl]] (English: [[Michael (archangel)|Michael]]),<ref>{{Cite quran|2|98|s=ns}}</ref> the archangel of mercy, is often depicted as providing nourishment for bodies and souls while also being responsible for bringing rain and thunder to Earth.<ref>Matthew L.N. Wilkinson ''A Fresh Look at Islam in a Multi-Faith World: A Philosophy for Success Through Education'' Routledge 2014 {{ISBN|978-1-317-59598-4}} page 106</ref> Some scholars pointed out that Mikail is in charge of angels who carry the laws of nature.<ref>Syrinx von Hees Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 320 (German)</ref>  According to legend, he was so shocked at the sight of hell when it was created that he never laughed again.\n* [[Israfil|Isr\u0101f\u012bl]] (frequently associated with the Jewish and Christian angel [[Raphael (archangel)|Raphael]]), is the archangel of music<ref>Sophy Burnham ''A Book of Angels: Reflections on Angels Past and Present, and True Stories of How They Touch Our Lives'' Penguin 2011 {{ISBN|978-1-101-48647-4}}</ref> often depicted with a trumpet, he will blow in the end time. Therefore, Israfil is responsible for signaling the coming of Qiyamah ([[Last Judgment|Judgment Day]]) by blowing a horn. On his association with Raphael, the historian Ali Olomi writes, \"In esoteric circles, Israfil is the angel of the West, the Sun, and sometimes Thursday. Other times the angel of Jupiter Sarfayail is assigned to Thursday. The astrological overlap may hint at a parallel with the Jewish angel Seraphiel or Raphael.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/aaolomi/status/1245411734971658247|title=In esoteric circles, Israfil is the angel of the West, the Sun, and sometimes Thursday. Other times the angel of Jupiter Sarfayail is assigned to Thursday. The astrological overlap may hint at a parallel with the Jewish angel Seraphiel or Raphael.|last=Olomi|first=Ali A.|date=2020-04-01|website=@aaolomi|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n* [[Azrael|'Azr\u0101'\u012bl/'Azrayl/Azrael]], is the [[Death (personification)|archangel of death]]. He and his subordinative angels are responsible for parting the soul from the body of the dead and will carry the believers to heaven ([[Illiyin]]) and the unbelievers to hell ([[Sijjin]]).<ref>Syrinx von Hees ''Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts'' Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 331 (German)</ref><ref>Juan Eduardo Campo ''Encyclopedia of Islam'' Infobase Publishing, 2009 {{ISBN|978-1-438-12696-8}} page 42</ref>\n\n===Mentioned in Quran===\n* [[N\u0101zi'\u0101t and N\u0101shi\u1e6d\u0101t]], helpers of Azrail who take the souls of the deceased.<ref>Quran 79:1-2</ref>\n* [[Hafaza]], (The [[Guardian angel]]):\n** [[Kiraman Katibin]] ([[Recording angel|Honourable Recorders]]),<ref>{{Cite quran|82|11|s=ns}}</ref> two of whom are charged to every human being; one writes down good deeds and another one writes down evil deeds. They are both described as 'Raqeebun 'Ateed' in the Qur'an. \n** [[Mu'aqqibat]] (The Protectors)<ref name=\"Cite quran|13|10|e=11|s=ns\">{{Cite quran|13|10|e=11|s=ns}}</ref> who keep people from death until its decreed time and who bring down blessings.\n* Angels of [[Hell]]:\n** [[Maalik]], Chief of the angels who govern [[Jahannam]] (Hell).\n** Nineteen angels of hell, commanding the [[Zabaniyya]], to torment sinful people in hell.\n* Those angels who distribute provisions, rain, and other blessings by God's Command.<ref>{{Cite quran|51|4|s=ns}}</ref>\n* Those angels who drive the clouds.<ref>{{Cite quran|37|2|s=ns}}</ref>\n* [[Bearers of the Throne|Hamalat al-'Arsh]], those who carry the 'Arsh ([[Throne of God]]),<ref>{{Cite quran|40|7|s=ns}}</ref> comparable to the Christian [[Seraph]].\n* [[Harut and Marut]],  often depicted as [[fallen angel#Islam|Fallen angel]]s who taught the humans in [[Babylon]] magic; mentioned in Quran (2:102).<ref>Hussein Abdul-Raof ''Theological Approaches to Qur'anic Exegesis: A Practical Comparative-Contrastive Analysis'' Routledge 2012 {{ISBN|978-1-136-45991-7}} page 155</ref>\n* [[Ar-Ra'd]], said to be the Angel of Thunder; mentioned in Quran (13:13). According to [[Tafsir al-Qurtubi]]: \"It is said that he is the angel in charge of clouds and he drives them as ordered by Allah, and he glorifies His Praises\".<ref>''The Noble Quran'', trans. Muhsin Khan; Taqi-ud-Din Hilali. See footnote to verse 13:13</ref>\n*The Angel of life gives the soul to every human being\n\n===In canonical hadith collections===\n* The angels of the [[Seven Heavens]].\n* Jundullah, those who helped Muhammad in the battlefield.\n* Those that give the spirit to the fetus in the womb and are charged with four commands: to write down his provision, his life-span, his actions, and whether he will be wretched or happy.<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|1|6|315}}</ref>\n*Malakul Jibaal(The Angel of the Mountains), met by the Prophet after his [[Muhammad's visit to Ta'if|ordeal at Taif]].<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|4|54|454}}</ref>\n* [[Munkar and Nakir]], who question the dead in their graves.<ref>[[Jami' at-Tirmidhi]] [https://sunnah.com/tirmidhi/10/ In-book reference\t : Book 10, Hadith 107 | English translation\t : Vol. 2, Book 5,  Hadith 1071]</ref>\n\n===Other===\n* [[Ridwan (angel)|Ridwan]], the keeper of [[Jannah|Paradise]].\n* [[Artiya'il]], the angel who removes grief and depression from the children of Adam.<ref name=\"burge angels1\">Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}}</ref>\n* [[Ishim (angel)#Islamic reception|Habib]], an angel [[Muhammad]] met during his night [[Isra and Mi'raj|journey]] composed of ice and fire.\n* The angels charged with each existent thing, maintaining order and warding off corruption. Their number is known only to God.<ref>''The Vision of Islam'' by [[Sachiko Murata]] & [[William Chittick]] pg 86-87</ref>\n* [[Darda'il]] (The Journeyers), who travel the earth searching out assemblies where people remember God's name.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110725235213/http://dinul-islam.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=102%3Ashirath-jembatan&catid=20%3Adaqoiqul-akhbar&Itemid=19 Darda'il on Dinul-islam.org]</ref>\n\n===Disputed===\n* [[Dhul-Qarnayn]], believed by some to be an angel or \"[[Angel|part-angel]]\" based on the statement of [[Umar bin Khattab]].<ref>Alfred Guillaume ''Ibn Ishaq's Sirat Rasul Allah''</ref>\n* [[Khidr]], sometimes regarded as an angel which took human form and thus able to reveal hidden knowledge exceeding those of the prophets to guide and help people or prophets.<ref>Brannon Wheeler ''Prophets in the Quran: An Introduction to the Quran and Muslim Exegesis'' A&C Black 2002 {{ISBN|978-0-826-44956-6}} page 225</ref>\n* [[Azazil]], in many early reports a former archangel, who was among whose who were commanded to bow before Adam, but he refused to and was banished to hell.\n\n==Sufism==\nAngels play an important role in Sufism. Just as in non-Sufi-related traditions, angels are thought of as created of light. [[Al-Jili]] specifies that the angels are created from the [[Logos (Islam)|Light of Muhammad]] and in his attribute of guidance, light and beauty.<ref>Awn, Peter J. (1983). Satan's Tragedy and Redemption: Ibl\u012bs in Sufi Psychology. Leiden, Germany: Brill Publishers. p. 182 {{ISBN|978-9004069060}}</ref> Influenced by [[Ibn Arabi]]s [[Sufi metaphysics]], [[Haydar Amuli]] identifies angels as created to represent different names/attributes of God's beauty, while the devils are created in accordance with God's attributes of Majesty, such as \"The Haugthy\" or \"The Domineering\".<ref>Ayman Shihadeh ''Sufism and Theology'' Edinburgh University Press, 21.11.2007 {{ISBN|9780748631346}} pp. 54-56</ref> [[Sufi cosmology]] divides the world into several realms. The realm of [[Malakut]] is the plane in which symbols take on form. It is also the sphere in which humans may encounter angels, during their dreams.<ref name=\"zein 50\">Amira El-Zein ''Islam, Arabs, and Intelligent World of the Jinn'' Syracuse University Press 2009 {{ISBN|9780815650706}} page 50</ref> Some authors have suggested that some individual angels in the microcosmos represent specific human faculties on a macrocosmic level.<ref>John Renard ''Historical Dictionary of Sufism'' Rowman & Littlefield, 19.11.2015 {{ISBN|9780810879744}} p. 38</ref> According to a common belief, if a Sufi can not find Shaikh to teach him, he will be taught by the angel [[Khidr]].<ref>Michael Anthony Sells ''Early Islamic Mysticism (CWS)'' Paulist Press 1996 {{ISBN|978-0-809-13619-3}} page 39</ref><ref>Noel Cobb ''Archetypal Imagination: Glimpses of the Gods in Life and Art'' SteinerBooks {{ISBN|978-0-940-26247-8}} page 194</ref>\n\n== Contemporary Era ==\n[[Wahhabism|Contemporary Salafism]] continues to regard the belief in angels as a pillar of Islam and regards the rejection of the literal belief in angels as [[kufr|unbelief]] and an [[Bid'ah|innovation]] brought by [[secularism]] and [[Positivism]]. Modern reinterpretations, as for example suggested by [[Nasr Abu Zayd]], are strongly disregarded. Simultaneously, many traditional materials regarding angels are rejected on the ground, they would not be authentic. The [[Muslim Brotherhood|Muslim Brotherhood scholars]] [[Sayyid Qutb]] and [[Umar Sulaiman Al-Ashqar]] reject much established material concerning angels, such as the story of ''Harut and Marut'' or naming the Angel of Death ''Azrail''. Sulayman Ashqar not only rejects the traditional material itself, further he disapproves scholars who used them.<ref>Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}} p. 13-14</ref>\n\n[[Islamic Modernism|Islamic Modernist scholars]] such as [[Muhammad Asad]] and [[Ghulam Ahmed Parwez]] have suggested a metaphorical reinterpretation of the concept of angels.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Guessoum|title=Islam's Quantum Question: Reconciling Muslim Tradition and Modern Science|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zaL3AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT165&dq=angels+islam+metaphor+science#v=snippet&q=angels&f=false|isbn=9780857730756|date=2010-10-30}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Angels in Islam}}\n* [[Angels in Judaism]]\n* [[Iblis]]\n* [[List of theological angels]]\n* [[List of theological demons]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Angels in Abrahamic Religions}}\n{{Characters and Names in Quran}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Islamic View Of Angels}}\n[[Category:Angels in Islam| ]]\n[[Category:Ritual purity in Islam|Angels]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Angels in Islamic tradition}}\n{{Islam |beliefs}}\n[[File:Islamic_angel,_persian_miniature.jpg|thumb|right|Angel in a [[Mughal miniature]], in the style of [[Bukhara]], 16th century]]\n[[File:'Angel Blowing a Woodwind', ink and opaque watercolor painting from Iran, c. 1500, Honolulu Academy of Arts.JPG|thumb|right|Angel Blowing a Woodwind', ink and opaque watercolor painting from Iran, c. 1500, Honolulu Academy of Arts]]\n\nIn Islam, [[angels]] ([[Arabic]]: {{lang|ar|{{large|\u0645\u0644\u0643}}}} ''{{transl|ar|DIN|malak}}''; plural: \u0645\u0644\u0627\u064b\u0626\u0650\u0643\u0629 ''mal\u0101'ikah'')<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia|author=Webb, Gisela | year= 2006 | title=Angel|encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02be\u0101n|editor=Jane Dammen McAuliffe|publisher=Brill| doi= 10.1163/1875-3922_q3_EQCOM_00010 }}{{subscription required}}</ref> are believed to be celestial beings, created from a luminous origin by [[God in Islam|God]]. They have different functions, including praising God in heavens, interacting with humans ordinary life, and carrying laws of nature. Islam acknowledges the concept of angels both as [[anthropomorphic]] and abstract.<ref name=\"burge angels1\">Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}}</ref> Belief in angels is one of the six [[Iman (concept)#The Six Articles of Faith|articles of faith]] in [[Islam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/islam/beliefs/beliefs.shtml|title=BBC - Religions - Islam: Basic articles of faith|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813005904/http://www.bbc.co.uk/religion/religions/islam/beliefs/beliefs.shtml|archive-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2018-08-13}}</ref> The Quran is the principal source for the Islamic concept of angels, but more extensive features of angels appear in [[hadith]]s, [[Isra and Mi'raj|Mi'raj literature]], [[kalam|Islamic theology]] and [[Islamic philosophy]].<ref>Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}} p. 22-23</ref> The angels differ from other spiritual creatures in their attitude as creatures of virtue in contrast to impure [[shaitan|demon]]s and morally ambivalent [[jinn]].<ref>Amira El-Zein Islam, Arabs, and Intelligent World of the Jinn Syracuse University Press 2009 {{ISBN|9780815650706}} page 20 </ref>\n\n==Corporeal angels==\n===Creation===\nAngels are another kind of creature created by God, known to mankind, commonly dwelling in the heavenly spheres. Although the Quran does not mention the time when angels were created, they are generally considered as the first creation of God. According to [[Tabari]], the angels had been created on Wednesday,<ref>Tobias N\u00fcnlist ''D\u00e4monenglaube im Islam'' Walter de Gruyter GmbH & Co KG, 2015 {{ISBN|978-3-110-33168-4}} p. 43 (German)</ref> while other creatures on the following days. Although not mentioned in the Quran,<ref>Jane Dammen McAuliffe Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02bc\u0101n Brill: VOlume 3, 2005 {{ISBN|9789004123564}} p. 45 </ref> angels are believed to be created from a luminous substance, repeatedly described as a form of light. The probably most famous [[hadith]] regarding their origin is reported in [[Sahih Muslim]]: \"The Angels were created out of light and the [[Jann (legendary creature)|Jann]] was created out of a mixture of fire and Adam was created out of what characterizes you.\"<ref>{{ cite web |title=\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0632\u0647\u062f \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0642\u0627\u0626\u0642 Book 55, Hadith 78. The Book of Zuhd and Softening of Hearts. (10) Chapter: Miscellaneous Ahadith(10) \u0628\u0627\u0628 \u0641\u0650\u064a \u0623\u064e\u062d\u064e\u0627\u062f\u0650\u064a\u062b\u064e \u0645\u064f\u062a\u064e\u0641\u064e\u0631\u0650\u0651\u0642\u064e\u0629\u064d |url=https://sunnah.com/muslim/55/78 |website=sunnah.com |accessdate=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page=100}}</ref> ''Nur'', the term used for the ''light'' from which the angels are created from, usually corresponds to the cold light of night or the light of the moon,<ref>Jane Dammen McAuliffe Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02bc\u0101n Brill: Volume 3, 2005 {{ISBN|9789004123564}} p. 45 </ref> contrasted to ''nar'', which corresponds to ''fire'' or the diurnal and solar light from which the angels of punishment are said to be created of.<ref>Jane Dammen McAuliffe Encyclopaedia of the Qur\u02be\u0101n Volume 5 Georgetown University, Washington DC p. 118</ref> Dividing angels into two groups created from different types of light is also attested by Tabari,<ref name=tafsir-al-tabiri-241>{{cite book |url=https://islaambooks.files.wordpress.com/2012/05/the-commentary-on-the-quran-volume-i-tafsir-al-tabari.pdf |last1=al-Tabari |title=Tafsir al-Tabiri |publisher=Islaam Books |page=241 |accessdate=16 March 2019}}</ref> [[Abd al-Ghani al-Maqdisi]],<ref>{{cite book |first1=Hamilton Alexander Rosskeen |last1=Gibb |title=The Encyclopaedia of Islam: NED-SAM |publisher=Brill |date=1995 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Encyclopaedia_of_Islam_NED_SAM.html?id=OO4pAQAAMAAJ |page=94}}</ref> [[Al-Jili]]<ref>Awn, Peter J. (1983). Satan's Tragedy and Redemption: Ibl\u012bs in Sufi Psychology. Leiden, Germany: Brill Publishers. p. 182 {{ISBN|978-9004069060}}.</ref> and [[Al-Suyuti]].<ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page= 58}}</ref> Suyuti distinguishes in his work [[Al-Hay\u2019a as-samya fi l-hay\u2019a as-sunmya]] angels as created from \"fire that eats, but does not drink\" in opposition to [[Shaitan|devils]] created from \"fire that drinks, but does not eat\" which is also identified with the fire of the sun.<ref>ANTON M. HEINEN ISLAMIC COSMOLOGY A STUDY OF AS-SUYUTI\u2019S al-Hay\u2019a as-samya fi l-hay\u2019a as-sunmya with critical edition, translation, and commentary ANTON M. HEINEN BEIRUT 1982 p. 143</ref> Scholars also argued that there is no distinction between ''nur'' and ''nar'' at all. Although not his conclusion, Tabari argued that both can be seen as the same substance, since both pass into each other but refer to the same thing on different degrees.<ref>Gauvain, Richard (2013). Salafi Ritual Purity: In the Presence of God. Abingdon, England: Routledge. p. 73. {{ISBN|978-0710313560}} p. 302</ref> Asserting that both fire and light are actually the same but on different degrees can also be found by [[Zakariya al-Qazwini|Qazwini]] and Ibishi.<ref>Syrinx von Hees Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 270</ref><ref>{{cite book |first1=Seyyed Hossein |last=Nasr |title=Islamic Life and Thought |publisher=Routledge |date=2013 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Islamic_life_and_thought.html?id=_jkNAQAAMAAJ |isbn=978-1-134-53818-8 |page=135}}</ref> The lack of distinction between fire and light might be explained by the fact that both are closely related [[Morphology (linguistics)|morphologically]] and [[Phonetics|phonetically]].<ref>Mustafa \u00d6ZT\u00dcRK ''JOURNAL OF ISLAMIC RESEARCH'' Vol 2 No 2 December 200</ref> [[Al-Baydawi]] argued that ''light'' serves only as a [[proverb]], but fire and light refers actually to the same substance.<ref>Houtsma, M. Th. (1993). E.J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936, Band 5. BRILL. p. 191. {{ISBN|978-9-004-09791-9}} p. 191</ref> Apart from light, other traditions also mention exceptions about angels created from fire, ice or water.<ref>Fr. Edmund Teuma, O.F.M. Conv ''THE NATURE OF \"IBLI$H IN THE QUR'AN AS INTERPRETED BY THE COMMENTATORS'' p. 16</ref>\n\n=== Characteristics ===\nOne of the Islamic major characteristic is their lack of bodily desires; they never get tired, do not eat or drink and have no anger.<ref name=\"glasse 49 50\"/> As with other monotheistic religions, angels are characteristics of their purity and obedience to God.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page=140}}</ref> However, their constant loyalty, towards God, emphasized by some Quranic verses such as {{cite quran|16|49|s=ns|b=n}}, does not necessarily imply [[impeccability]],<ref name=\"houtsma 191\"/> and the motif of erring angels is also known to Islam.<ref>[[Christoph Auffarth]], [[Loren T. Stuckenbruck]] ''The Fall of the Angels'' BRILL 2004 {{ISBN|978-9-004-12668-8}} page 161</ref> Some scholars on the other hand, among [[Hasan of Basra]] as one of the first,<ref>Omar Hamdan ''Studien Zur Kanonisierung des Korantextes: al-\u1e24asan al-Ba\u1e63r\u012bs Beitr\u00e4ge Zur Geschichte des Korans'' Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2006 {{ISBN|978-3-447-05349-5}} page 292 (German)</ref> extend their loyalty towards God to assume general impeccability. Those who accept the possibility of erring angels, advocate that actually only the messengers among the angels are infallible,<ref>Fr. Edmund Teuma THE NATURE OF \"IBLI$H IN THE QUR'AN AS INTERPRETED BY THE COMMENTATORS University of Malta p. 15-16</ref> since the Quran also describes angels as being tested.<ref>http://www.dinimizislam.com/detay.asp?Aid=3563</ref> [[Al-Baydawi]] argued, that angels only remain impeccable if they do not fall. [[Ibn Arabi]] stated that angels may err in opposing Adam as a vice-regent and fixing on their way of worshipping God to the exclusion of other creatures.<ref>Sa'diyya Shaikh ''Sufi Narratives of Intimacy: Ibn Arabi, Gender, and Sexuality'' Univ of North Carolina Press 2012 {{ISBN|978-0-807-83533-3}} page 114</ref><ref>Christian Krokus ''The Theology of Louis Massignon'' CUA Press 2017 {{ISBN|978-0-813-22946-1}} page 89</ref>\n\nAngels are usually described in [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic forms]] combined with supernatural images, such as wings, being of great size, wearing heavenly clothes and great beauty.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page=99}}</ref> Some angels are identified with specific colors, often with white, but some special angels have a distinct color, such as Gabriel being associated with the color green.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Stephen |last1=Burge |title=Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi akhbar al-mala'ik |publisher=Routledge |date=2015 |isbn=978-1-136-50473-0 |page=113}}</ref>\n\nScholars debated whether human or angels rank higher. The prostration of angels before [[Adam in Islam|Adam]] is often seen as evidence for humans' supremacy over angels. Nevertheless, other hold angels to be superior, as being free from  material deficits, such as anger and lust, Angels are free from such inferior urges and therefore superior, a position especially found among [[Mu'tazilites]] and some [[Asharites]].<ref name=\"houtsma 191\">{{cite book |first1=M. Th. |last1=Houtsma |title=E.J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936, Band 5 |publisher=BRILL |date=1993 \n |isbn=978-9-004-09791-9 |page=191}}</ref> A similar opinion was asserted by Hasan of Basri, who argued that angels are superior to humans due to their infallibility, originally opposed by both [[Sunnism|Sunnis]] and [[Shia]]s.<ref>Omar Hamdan Studien Zur Kanonisierung des Korantextes: al-\u1e24asan al-Ba\u1e63r\u012bs Beitr\u00e4ge Zur Geschichte des Korans Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2006 {{ISBN|978-3-447-05349-5}} page 293 (German)</ref> This view is based on the assumption of superiority of pure spirit against body and flesh. Contrarily argued, humans rank above angels, since for a human it is harder to be obedient and to worship God, hassling with bodily temptations, in contrast to angels, whose life is much easier and therefore their obedience is rather insignificant. Islam acknowledges a famous story about competing angels and humans in the tale of [[Harut and Marut]], who were tested to determine, whether or not, angels would do better than humans under the same circumstances,<ref>Patricia Crone THE BOOK OF WATCHERS IN THE QUR\u00c5N page 11</ref> a tradition opposed by later scholars, such as [[ibn Taimiyya]], but still accepted by earlier scholars, such as [[ibn Hanbal]].<ref>Reynolds, Gabriel Said, \u201cAngels\u201d, in: Encyclopaedia of Islam, THREE, Edited by: Kate Fleet, Gudrun Kr\u00e4mer, Denis Matringe, John Nawas, Everett Rowson. Consulted online on 16 October 2019 <http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/1573-3912_ei3_COM_23204> Erste Online-Erscheinung: 2009 Erste Druckedition: 9789004181304, 2009, 2009-3</ref> Some [[Sufism|Sufi traditions]] argue that a human generally ranks below angels, but developed to [[Al-Ins\u0101n al-K\u0101mil]], he ranks above angels.<ref>Mohamed Haj Yousef The Single Monad Model of the Cosmos: Ibn Arabi's Concept of Time and Creation ibnalarabi 2014 {{ISBN|978-1-499-77984-4}} page 292</ref> Comparable to another major opinion, that prophets and messengers among humans rank above angels, but the ordinary human below an angel, while the messengers among angels rank higher than prophets.<ref name=\"houtsma 191\"/> [[Maturidism]] generally holds that angels' and prophets' superiority and obedience derive from their virtues and insights to God's action, but not as their original purity.<ref>Ulrich Rudolph Al-M\u0101tur\u012bd\u012b und Die Sunnitische Theologie in Samarkand BRILL, 1997 {{ISBN|9789004100237}} pp. 54-56</ref>\n\n=== Purity ===\nAngels believed to be engaged in human affairs are closely related to Islamic purity and modesty rituals. Many [[hadith]]s, including [[Muwatta Imam Malik]] from one of the [[Kutub al-Sittah]], talk about angels being repelled by humans' state of impurity.<ref>Burge, S. R. \u201cImpurity / Danger!\u201d Islamic Law and Society, vol. 17, no. 3-4, 2010, pp. 320\u2013349. JSTOR, https://www.jstor.org/stable/23034917.p. 323</ref> Such angels keep a distance from humans, who polluted themselves by certain actions (such as sexual intercourse). However, angels might return to an individual as soon as the person (ritually) purified himself or herself. The absence of angels may cause several problems for the person. If driven away by ritual impurity, the [[Kiraman Katibin]], who record people's actions,<ref>Burge, S. R. \u201cImpurity / Danger!\u201d Islamic Law and Society, vol. 17, no. 3-4, 2010, pp. 320\u2013349. JSTOR, https://www.jstor.org/stable/23034917.p. 325</ref> and the [[Guardian angel]],<ref>Burge, S. R. \u201cImpurity / Danger!\u201d Islamic Law and Society, vol. 17, no. 3-4, 2010, pp. 320\u2013349. JSTOR, https://www.jstor.org/stable/23034917.p. 327</ref> will not perform their tasks assigned to the individual. Another hadith specifies, during the state of impurity, bad actions are still written down, but good actions are not. When a person tells a lie, angels nearly are separated from the person from the stench it emanates.<ref>Burge, S. R. \u201cImpurity / Danger!\u201d Islamic Law and Society, vol. 17, no. 3-4, 2010, pp. 320\u2013349. JSTOR, https://www.jstor.org/stable/23034917.328</ref> Angels also depart from humans when they are naked or are having a bath out of decency, but also curse people who are nude in public.\n\n== Abstract angels ==\n=== Philosophy ===\nIn Islamic philosophy, angels appear frequently as incorporeal creatures. [[Al-Kindi]] and [[Ibn Sina]] both define angels as simple substances, which means, they belong to the [[Celestial spheres]] comparable to [[Ptolemaic astronomy]], endowed with life, reason, and immortality, in contrast to sublunary entities such as humans and animals, who are endowed with life, and the former also with reason, but are mortal.<ref>Seyyed Hossein Nasr ''An Introduction to Islamic Cosmological Doctrines'' SUNY Press, 01.01.1993 {{ISBN|9780791415153}} p. 236</ref><ref>Syrinx von Hees Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 268 (German)</ref> Similar Qazwini assigns the angels to heavenly spheres, distinguishing them from among the animals, although both are said to possess the attribute of life. Significantly, [[Al-Damiri]] includes in his [[zoology|zoological]] works, animals, humans, [[jinn]] and even demons, but not angels.<ref>Houtsma, M. Th. (1993). E.J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam, 1913-1936, Band 5. BRILL. p. 191. {{ISBN|978-9-004-09791-9}} p. 192</ref> Such cosmological thought, maintained by scholars such as [[Al-Farabi]] and Ibn Sina, has strong resemblance with the [[Neoplatonism|Neo-Platonistic]] [[Emanationism|emanation cosmology]], identifying the different angels in Islam with [[Nous|intellects]], dividing the cosmos into different spheres. However, Islamic scholars repeatedly insist that all heavenly spheres as a whole form a single body and are moved by God, in contrast to Aristotelian cosmology in which God only moves the outer sphere.<ref>Seyyed Hossein Nasr ''An Introduction to Islamic Cosmological Doctrines'' SUNY Press, 01.01.1993 {{ISBN|9780791415153}} p. 236</ref> According to ibn Sina, but differing from Al-Farabi, God is not part of the scheme of emanation. God emanated things in accordance with his will. In his ''Theologia Aristotelis'' he shows that through the manifestation of God, the intellects are aware of God and their role in the universe. Further Ibn Sina seems to distinguishes between two types of angels: One completely unrelated to matter, and another one, which exists in form of a superior kind of matter. The latter ones can carry messages between the heavenly spheres and the sublunary world, appearing in visions. Therefore, the higher angels dwell in [[Jabarut|higher spheres]], while their subordinate angels appear in an [[Malakut|intermediary realm]]. Ibn Sina's explanation might imply an attempt to consider revelation as part of the natural world.<ref name=\"glasse 49 50\">Cyril Glass\u00e9, Huston Smith, The New Encyclopedia of Islam Rowman Altamira 2003 {{ISBN|978-0-759-10190-6}} page 49-50</ref><ref>Abd Al-Jabbar, Ibn Sina and Al-Ghazali ''God and Humans in Islamic Thought'' Routledge 2006 {{ISBN|9780203965375}}  p. 97</ref> Also Qazwini lists a lower type of angels; earthly angels as indwelling forces of nature, who keep the world in order and never deviate from their duty. Qazwini believed that the existence of these angels could be proved by reason and effects of these angels on their assigned object.<ref>Syrinx von Hees Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 263</ref>\n\n=== Psychology ===\n{{Expand section | date=August 2019}}\nIslamic philosophy stressed that humans own angelic and demonic qualities and that the human soul is seen as a ''potential angel'' or ''potential [[Shaitan|demon]]''.<ref>Amira El-Zein Islam, Arabs, and Intelligent World of the Jinn Syracuse University Press 2009 {{ISBN|978-0-815-65070-6}} page 43</ref> Depending on whether the [[nafs|sensual soul]] or the [[Ruh|rational soul]] develop, the human soul becomes an angel or a demon.<ref>Khaled El-Rouayheb, Sabine Schmidtke The Oxford Handbook of Islamic Philosophy Oxford University Press 2016 {{ISBN|978-0-199-91739-6}} page 186</ref> Angels may also give inspirations opposite to the evil suggestions, called ''wasw\u0101s'', from [[Satan]].<ref name=\"thoughtco1\">https://www.thoughtco.com/angels-in-islam-2004030</ref>\n\n== In Ibn Abbas Mi'raj narrative ==\n[[File:Maalik_opens_the_gates_of_hell.jpg|thumb|Muhammad requests Maalik to show him Hell during his heavenly journey. Miniature from [[The David Collection]].]]\n[[File:Muhammad_encountering_the_angel_of_fire_and_ice.jpg|thumb|Muhammad encounters the Angel composed of fire and ice during his [[Isra and Mi'raj|Night journey]]. Miniature from a copy of al-Sarai\u2019s ''Nahj al-Faradis'' from [[The David Collection]]]]\n\n[[Muhammad]]'s encounter with several significant angels on his [[Isra and Mi'raj|journey through the celestial spheres]], play a major role in [[Ibn Abbas]] version.<ref>Hajjah Amina Adil (2012). \"Ezra\". ''Muhammad the Messenger of Islam: His life & prophecy''. BookBaby. {{ISBN|978-1-618-42913-1}}.</ref><ref>name=\"State University of New York Press\">{{cite book|last1=Colby|first1=Frederick S|title=Narrating Muhammad's Night Journey: Tracing the Development of the Ibn 'Abbas Ascension Discourse|date=2008|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-7914-7518-8}}</ref> Many scholars such as [[Al-Tha`labi]] drew their exegesis upon this narrative, however it never led to an established angelology as known in Christianity.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! first heaven !! second heaven !! third heaven !! fourth heaven !! fifth heaven !! sixth heaven !! seventh heaven\n|-\n| [[Ishim (angel)|Habib]] || [[Azrael|Angel of Death]] || [[Maalik]] || Salsa'il || [[Kalqa'il]] || [[Michael (archangel)|Mikha'il]] (Archangel) || [[Israfil]]\n|-\n| Rooster angel || [[N\u0101zi'\u0101t and N\u0101shi\u1e6d\u0101t|Angels of death]] || Angel with seventy heads || Angels of the sun || - || [[Cherub]]im || [[Bearers of the Throne]]\n|-\n| [[Ri\u1e0dwan|Ismail (or ''Ri\u1e0dwan'')]] || Mika'il || Arina'il || - || - || Shamka'il || Afra'il\n|}\n\n==Individual angels==\nIslam has no standard hierarchical organization that parallels the [[Christian angelic hierarchy|division into different \"choirs\" or spheres]] hypothesized and drafted by early medieval [[Christian theology|Christian theologians]], but does distinguish between archangels and angels. Angels are not equal in status and consequently, they are delegated different tasks to perform.\n\n===Archangels===\n* [[Holy Spirit (Islam)#As interpreted to refer to the Archangel Gabriel|Jibra'il/Jibril/Jabril]] ([[Judeo-Christian]]: [[Gabriel]]),<ref>Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}} chapter 3</ref> the angel of revelation. Jibra'il is the archangel responsible for revealing the Quran to  [[Muhammad]], verse by verse. Jibra'il is the angel who communicates with (all of) the prophets and also descends with the blessings of God during the night of [[Laylat al-Qadr]] (\"The Night of Divine Destiny (Fate)\"). Jibra'il is also acknowledged as a magnificent warrior in Islamic tradition, who led an army of angels into the [[Battle of Badr]] and fought against Iblis as he tempted Jesus (Isa).<ref>Islam Issa ''Milton in the Arab-Muslim World'' Taylor & Francis 2016 {{ISBN|978-1-317-09592-7}} page 111</ref>\n* [[Michael (archangel)|Mikail]], also spelled M\u012bk\u0101l or M\u012bk\u0101\u02be\u012bl (Judeo-Christian: [[Michael (archangel)|Michael]]),<ref>{{Cite quran|2|98|s=ns}}</ref> the archangel of mercy, is often depicted as providing nourishment for bodies and souls while also being responsible for bringing rain and thunder to Earth.<ref>Matthew L.N. Wilkinson ''A Fresh Look at Islam in a Multi-Faith World: A Philosophy for Success Through Education'' Routledge 2014 {{ISBN|978-1-317-59598-4}} page 106</ref> Some scholars pointed out that Mikail is in charge of angels who carry the laws of nature.<ref>Syrinx von Hees Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 320 (German)</ref>  According to legend, he was so shocked at the sight of hell when it was created that he never laughed again.\n* [[Israfil]] or [[Israfil|Israafiyl]] (Judeo-Christian: [[Raphael (archangel)|Raphael]]), is the archangel of music<ref>Sophy Burnham ''A Book of Angels: Reflections on Angels Past and Present, and True Stories of How They Touch Our Lives'' Penguin 2011 {{ISBN|978-1-101-48647-4}}</ref> often depicted with a trumpet, he will blow in the end time. Therefore, Israfil is responsible for signaling the coming of Qiyamah ([[Last Judgment|Judgment Day]]) by blowing a horn.\n* [[Azrael|'Azrail/'Azrayl/Azrael]], is the [[Death (personification)|archangel of death]]. He and his subordinative angels are responsible for parting the soul from the body of the dead and will carry the believers to heaven ([[Illiyin]]) and the unbelievers to hell ([[Sijjin]]).<ref>Syrinx von Hees ''Enzyklop\u00e4die als Spiegel des Weltbildes: Qazw\u012bn\u012bs Wunder der Sch\u00f6pfung: eine Naturkunde des 13. Jahrhunderts'' Otto Harrassowitz Verlag 2002 {{ISBN|978-3-447-04511-7}} page 331 (German)</ref><ref>Juan Eduardo Campo ''Encyclopedia of Islam'' Infobase Publishing, 2009 {{ISBN|978-1-438-12696-8}} page 42</ref>\n\n===Mentioned in Quran===\n* [[N\u0101zi'\u0101t and N\u0101shi\u1e6d\u0101t]], helpers of Azrail who take the souls of the deceased.<ref>Quran 79:1-2</ref>\n* [[Hafaza]], (The [[Guardian angel]]):\n** [[Kiraman Katibin]] ([[Recording angel|Honourable Recorders]]),<ref>{{Cite quran|82|11|s=ns}}</ref> two of whom are charged to every human being; one writes down good deeds and another one writes down evil deeds. They are both described as 'Raqeebun 'Ateed' in the Qur'an. \n** [[Mu'aqqibat]] (The Protectors)<ref name=\"Cite quran|13|10|e=11|s=ns\">{{Cite quran|13|10|e=11|s=ns}}</ref> who keep people from death until its decreed time and who bring down blessings.\n* Angels of [[Hell]]:\n** [[Maalik]], Chief of the angels who govern [[Jahannam]] (Hell).\n** Nineteen angels of hell, commanding the [[Zabaniyya]], to torment sinful people in hell.\n* Those angels who distribute provisions, rain, and other blessings by God's Command.<ref>{{Cite quran|51|4|s=ns}}</ref>\n* Those angels who drive the clouds.<ref>{{Cite quran|37|2|s=ns}}</ref>\n* [[Bearers of the Throne|Hamalat al-'Arsh]], those who carry the 'Arsh ([[Throne of God]]),<ref>{{Cite quran|40|7|s=ns}}</ref> comparable to the Christian [[Seraph]].\n* [[Harut and Marut]],  often depicted as [[fallen angel#Islam|Fallen angel]]s who taught the humans in [[Babylon]] magic; mentioned in Quran (2:102).<ref>Hussein Abdul-Raof ''Theological Approaches to Qur'anic Exegesis: A Practical Comparative-Contrastive Analysis'' Routledge 2012 {{ISBN|978-1-136-45991-7}} page 155</ref>\n* [[Ar-Ra'd]], said to be the Angel of Thunder; mentioned in Quran (13:13). According to [[Tafsir al-Qurtubi]]: \"It is said that he is the angel in charge of clouds and he drives them as ordered by Allah, and he glorifies His Praises\".<ref>''The Noble Quran'', trans. Muhsin Khan; Taqi-ud-Din Hilali. See footnote to verse 13:13</ref>\n*The Angel of life gives the soul to every human being\n\n===In canonical hadith collections===\n* The angels of the [[Seven Heavens]].\n* Jundullah, those who helped Muhammad in the battlefield.\n* Those that give the spirit to the fetus in the womb and are charged with four commands: to write down his provision, his life-span, his actions, and whether he will be wretched or happy.<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|1|6|315}}</ref>\n*Malakul Jibaal(The Angel of the Mountains), met by the Prophet after his [[Muhammad's visit to Ta'if|ordeal at Taif]].<ref>{{Hadith-usc|bukhari|usc=yes|4|54|454}}</ref>\n* [[Munkar and Nakir]], who question the dead in their graves.<ref>[[Jami' at-Tirmidhi]] [https://sunnah.com/tirmidhi/10/ In-book reference\t : Book 10, Hadith 107 | English translation\t : Vol. 2, Book 5,  Hadith 1071]</ref>\n\n===Other===\n* [[Ridwan (angel)|Ridwan]], the keeper of [[Jannah|Paradise]].\n* [[Artiya'il]], the angel who removes grief and depression from the children of Adam.<ref name=\"burge angels1\">Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}}</ref>\n* [[Ishim (angel)#Islamic reception|Habib]], an angel [[Muhammad]] met during his night [[Isra and Mi'raj|journey]] composed of ice and fire.\n* The angels charged with each existent thing, maintaining order and warding off corruption. Their number is known only to God.<ref>''The Vision of Islam'' by [[Sachiko Murata]] & [[William Chittick]] pg 86-87</ref>\n* [[Darda'il]] (The Journeyers), who travel the earth searching out assemblies where people remember God's name.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110725235213/http://dinul-islam.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=102%3Ashirath-jembatan&catid=20%3Adaqoiqul-akhbar&Itemid=19 Darda'il on Dinul-islam.org]</ref>\n\n===Disputed===\n* [[Dhul-Qarnayn]], believed by some to be an angel or \"[[Angel|part-angel]]\" based on the statement of [[Umar bin Khattab]].<ref>Alfred Guillaume ''Ibn Ishaq's Sirat Rasul Allah''</ref>\n* [[Khidr]], sometimes regarded as an angel which took human form and thus able to reveal hidden knowledge exceeding those of the prophets to guide and help people or prophets.<ref>Brannon Wheeler ''Prophets in the Quran: An Introduction to the Quran and Muslim Exegesis'' A&C Black 2002 {{ISBN|978-0-826-44956-6}} page 225</ref>\n* [[Azazil]], in many early reports a former archangel, who was among whose who were commanded to bow before Adam, but he refused to and was banished to hell.\n\n==Sufism==\nAngels play an important role in Sufism. Just as in non-Sufi-related traditions, angels are thought of as created of light. [[Al-Jili]] specifies that the angels are created from the [[Logos (Islam)|Light of Muhammad]] and in his attribute of guidance, light and beauty.<ref>Awn, Peter J. (1983). Satan's Tragedy and Redemption: Ibl\u012bs in Sufi Psychology. Leiden, Germany: Brill Publishers. p. 182 {{ISBN|978-9004069060}}</ref> Influenced by [[Ibn Arabi]]s [[Sufi metaphysics]], [[Haydar Amuli]] identifies angels as created to represent different names/attributes of God's beauty, while the devils are created in accordance with God's attributes of Majesty, such as \"The Haugthy\" or \"The Domineering\".<ref>Ayman Shihadeh ''Sufism and Theology'' Edinburgh University Press, 21.11.2007 {{ISBN|9780748631346}} pp. 54-56</ref> [[Sufi cosmology]] divides the world into several realms. The realm of [[Malakut]] is the plane in which symbols take on form. It is also the sphere in which humans may encounter angels, during their dreams.<ref name=\"zein 50\">Amira El-Zein ''Islam, Arabs, and Intelligent World of the Jinn'' Syracuse University Press 2009 {{ISBN|9780815650706}} page 50</ref> Some authors have suggested that some individual angels in the microcosmos represent specific human faculties on a macrocosmic level.<ref>John Renard ''Historical Dictionary of Sufism'' Rowman & Littlefield, 19.11.2015 {{ISBN|9780810879744}} p. 38</ref> According to a common belief, if a Sufi can not find Shaikh to teach him, he will be taught by the angel [[Khidr]].<ref>Michael Anthony Sells ''Early Islamic Mysticism (CWS)'' Paulist Press 1996 {{ISBN|978-0-809-13619-3}} page 39</ref><ref>Noel Cobb ''Archetypal Imagination: Glimpses of the Gods in Life and Art'' SteinerBooks {{ISBN|978-0-940-26247-8}} page 194</ref>\n\n== Contemporary Era ==\n[[Wahhabism|Contemporary Salafism]] continues to regard the belief in angels as a pillar of Islam and regards the rejection of the literal belief in angels as [[kufr|unbelief]] and an [[Bid'ah|innovation]] brought by [[secularism]] and [[Positivism]]. Modern reinterpretations, as for example suggested by [[Nasr Abu Zayd]], are strongly disregarded. Simultaneously, many traditional materials regarding angels are rejected on the ground, they would not be authentic. The [[Muslim Brotherhood|Muslim Brotherhood scholars]] [[Sayyid Qutb]] and [[Umar Sulaiman Al-Ashqar]] reject much established material concerning angels, such as the story of ''Harut and Marut'' or naming the Angel of Death ''Azrail''. Sulayman Ashqar not only rejects the traditional material itself, further he disapproves scholars who used them.<ref>Stephen Burge ''Angels in Islam: Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti's al-Haba'ik fi Akhbar al-malik'' Routledge 2015 {{ISBN|978-1-136-50473-0}} p. 13-14</ref>\n\n[[Islamic Modernism|Islamic Modernist scholars]] such as [[Muhammad Asad]] and [[Ghulam Ahmed Parwez]] have suggested a metaphorical reinterpretation of the concept of angels.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Guessoum|title=Islam's Quantum Question: Reconciling Muslim Tradition and Modern Science|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zaL3AgAAQBAJ&pg=PT165&dq=angels+islam+metaphor+science#v=snippet&q=angels&f=false|isbn=9780857730756|date=2010-10-30}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Angels in Islam}}\n* [[Angels in Judaism]]\n* [[Iblis]]\n* [[List of theological angels]]\n* [[List of theological demons]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Angels in Abrahamic Religions}}\n{{Characters and Names in Quran}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Islamic View Of Angels}}\n[[Category:Angels in Islam| ]]\n[[Category:Ritual purity in Islam|Angels]]\n", "name_user": "Qenc", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected transliterations, and changed \"Judeo-Christian\" to \"English\" because Gabriel is simply Jibril in English for people of many different religions, and same thing with Jibril being Gabriel in Arabic. Provided more information of Israfil's relationship to Raphael (it's not 1-to-1 like Gibril & Gabriel.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angels_in_Islam"}
